<HEAD>Columnist To Face Weapons Possession Charges, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA WOMACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syndicated columnist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> will face weapons possession charges after shooting a teen-ager who had taken an unauthorized predawn dip in <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>'s backyard swimming pool, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday night. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said in its Friday editions that <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> was charged with possession of an unregistered handgun and unregistered ammunition in District of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Layton </PERSON>, director of communications for the <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> government, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that officials refused to comment on the the case until Friday, when a statement will be issued. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>, 62, was cleared of assault charges in the case on June 23 after an investigation by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said at the time that he believed <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> should be prosecuted for possessing an unregistered handgun. But <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> deferred that decision to the city, which normally decides whether to prosecute such cases. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>, who has frequently written columns calling for strict restrictions on handgun use, was out of town and unavailable for comment. His wife, <PERSON> Vivian </PERSON>, said the couple had no knowledge of the charges against <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said it had been told by <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> office of corporation counsel, which under local law has the authority to prosecute cases involving unregistered firearms, that <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> was charged on Wednesday. The shooting renewed debate on handgun restrictions, as pro-gun groups accused <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> of hypocrisy for owning a gun after publicly opposing the practice. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> said he obtained the weapon after receiving death threats. If convicted on the charges, the columnist faces a maximum penalty of two years in jail and a $ 2,000 fine in connection with the June 14 incident at his northwest <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> home. The District of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s 1976 handgun ordinance requires that all weapons be registered, but <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> told authorities that the gun had belonged to his son, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> claimed that his son was told he did not have to register the weapon after leaving the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> told authorities that he shot <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 18, of <LOCATION> Chevy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, after hearing noises in his back yard, calling police and discovering <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and three other youths by his pool. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> said he shot <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> after the teen-ager lunged at him. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> disputed that, saying he did not threaten the columnist and was shot while trying to flee. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who was wounded in the wrist, was treated and released the same day from <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. He and and a companion were each charged with one count of unlawful entry stemming from their foray onto <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>'s property, but prosecutors dropped the misdemeanor charges in exchange for 40 hours of community service work from both.
