<HEAD>Officer Kills Man Accused Of Robbery Outside St. Patrick's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man robbed a tourist at gunpoint on crowded Fifth Avenue outside <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Patrick </LOCATION>'s Cathedral, then was shot and killed Wednesday when he tried to escape in a car driven by an off-duty correction officer, police said. During a struggle inside the car, the correction officer fired his gun, striking the robbery suspect three times in the chest, said a police spokesman, Sgt. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. The suspect, <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON>, 22, of Queens died later in the afternoon at <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. The correction officer, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>, 33, also shot himself in the foot during the struggle and was in stable condition at <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> fired no shots, but police recovered a revolver, believed to be <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>'s, that contained five live rounds, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>'s 5-year-old son, also named <PERSON> John </PERSON>, was in the car at the time of the 5 p.m. shooting but was not injured, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. A second robbery suspect was still at large, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashcraft </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, said he was visiting midtown <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> with his family, standing on the sidewalk photographing the historic Roman Catholic cathedral, when two men pulled up in a car and one got out and demanded his video camera. `` He said if you do n't give me your camera and take it over and put it in that car right now I'm going to shoot you. At that point I did n't believe he had a gun,'' said <PERSON> Ashcraft </PERSON>. `` But then he pulled the gun and when he pulled the gun I gave him the camera,'' <PERSON> Ashcraft </PERSON> said. As the robbers tried to speed off, their car collided with a taxi and then slammed into the side of a bus. The pair then jumped out of their car and fled on foot before <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> got into <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON>'s car, police said. The gun used by <PERSON> Bonilla </PERSON> was his personal revolver, which he was authorized to carry, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ashcraft </PERSON> recovered his video camera from the robbery suspects' car, where they had left it behind when they fled, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said `` We've been riding the subways every place we go and not had a fear in the world,'' said <PERSON> Ashcraft </PERSON>, who was with his wife, their 6-year-old daughter and 9-year-old son and Mrs. <PERSON> Ashcraft </PERSON>'s uncle. Now, he said, `` I'm a little afraid.'' But he said he would n't consider <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> `` a bad place. It's just one incident.''
