<SECOND>AM-Ireland Pilgrimage,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>O'Connor Disagrees With Koch On British In N. Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, breaking with fellow peace pilgrim Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, said Wednesday that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> should remove its `` occupying forces'' from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> `` within a reasonable time.'' `` I can not imagine there will be lasting peace ... until all British troops have withdrawn,'' he told reporters as he left <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> after a six-day peace pilgrimage. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> had said at the start of the pilgrimage that he'd come to pray, not to talk politics. But the cardinal broke his silence after <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, his pilgrimage companion, reversed himself and endorsed the British presence in <LOCATION> Ulster </LOCATION>. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, who returned Wednesday afternoon to <LOCATION> John </LOCATION> <LOCATION> F. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, called on <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> officials to announce `` a phased withdrawal'' _ one the cardinal said was supported by most people in the province. Asked if it should begin immediately, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> replied, `` That's not for me to say. Before leaving <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION> on Tuesday, <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said a day in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> had convinced him the British do not deserve `` the castigation that many of us, myself included, have heaped upon them. The British army is not an ` occupation force,' -LRB- but rather -RRB- a guardian of peace.'' The British army has patrolled <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> since the early 1970s, when a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> civil rights movement came under attack by <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> police and paramilitary groups. But the Protestant violence also revitalized the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>; since then, the primary opponents have been the British and the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>, which wants to unite the island. In recent years many British troops have been withdrawn, and their duties assumed by members of Ulster's army reserve. About two-thirds of <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s population is Protestant, and surveys indicate that a majority of the province's residents _ including many Catholics _ favor union with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said his own 24 hours in Ulster convinced him there is `` an environment of increasing understanding'' between Catholics and Protestants, and that `` an overwhelming number'' of both want the troops out. Although <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said he based his conclusion on talks with Protestants, he did not meet with militants in either community during his visit. The mayor's comments drew a heated response from Irish-American politicians, including <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Comptroller <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, who called the remarks `` senseless and ridiculous.'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> was more circumspect. He said he was not angry with <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, and felt that because <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> did not grow up as an Irish-American, he failed to realize the British have been calling themselves peacemakers in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> for centuries.
