<HEAD>Billboards Against Beggars May Hurt El Paso Image, Critics Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four highway billboards that urge motorists not to give to street beggars have drawn some uncharitable comments from the city's <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, which worries the advertisements may hurt El Paso's image. `` I'm concerned -LRB- they -RRB- may not do good service to the fact that this city is a truly giving city,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` It does n't portray us as the kind of city I know us to be.'' An anonymous group paid for four billboards along Interstate 10 that read: `` Please do n't give to beggars _ they cause traffic problems.'' The signs are the latest development in a controversy about street beggars who cross the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, and panhandle on interstate access roads east of downtown. City Councilman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Candelaria </PERSON>, who participated in several council discussions about the scores of beggars congregating at access road intersections, said people who give encourage panhandlers to return. He said givers can contribute in other ways. `` We feel sorry for the people, but they endanger their lives by crossing near I-10,'' <PERSON> Candelaria </PERSON> said. `` Give your charitable dollars to Project Hungry before you give to these beggars.'' Some witnesses told the council earlier this month that panhandlers often are employed by Juarez-based professional begging rings, and that they often are not as needy as they seem. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Huff </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Bauman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the billboards, said the group that paid for the ads wishes to remain anonymous. The ads cost about $ 1,200 and will be visible for about two weeks, he said.
