me Khmer -LRB- <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> -RRB- factions are equally heavily responsible for these miseries and humilations.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in December 1978 and ousted the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime of <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>, which gained control at the end of the war and had killed hundreds of thousands of Cambodians. More than 100,000 Vietnamese soldiers remain in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, fighting the resistance coalition <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> formerly led. <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has said it will withdraw all its troops by early 1990. The prince called for an interim government of the four factions under `` a collegial system perfectly equal,'' and proposed that fighting units be kept intact under a general staff representing all factions. Each government department would have four co-ministers. An international conference convened under the auspices of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general would supervise withdrawal of foreign forces, guarantee the nation's neutrality and help organize free elections. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> resigned earlier this month as head of the resistance coalition and is in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> as a guest of President <PERSON> Suharto </PERSON>, which allows him to participate in the peace talks indirectly. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> presented his own peace plan at <LOCATION> Bogor </LOCATION> on Monday, and <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> said his proposals include some of its points. `` I think my proposal is the most realistic,'' he said. `` The very solution is in my proposals, not those of the charming <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>. I have to reject all other proposals in favor of mine.'' He and <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> negotiated in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> last December and January without finding a formula for peace. Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> said he supported <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s plan but the other participants were not available for comment. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Co </PERSON> <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> told a news conference Wednesday that working groups would be formed to prepare for further negotiations. No conclusive agreement had been expected from the <LOCATION> Bogor </LOCATION> conference, which was considered a success for merely taking place.
