<HEAD>Mortgage Subsidies to Rural Poor Prove Cost-Effective, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Low-income rural homeowners who receive federal mortgage subsidies have excellent repayment records and benefit from a more stable family life, a private study of 894 households has found. The study by the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> also said the <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s low-income home ownership program is cost-effective and should be expanded. Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said the study released Wednesday proves the program has succeeded in `` the very toughest, hardscrabble places'' and that the poor are neither lazy nor irresponsible and hopeless. `` After all of the attacks on housing assistance programs, this study shows what really happens with subsidized homeownership programs. ... These programs work,'' said <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on housing. Subsidies to participants in the program declined over a five-year period as their incomes increased, and the number of children living below the poverty level decreased, the study said. The council tracked 894 sample families nationwide who obtained subsizied mortgages in 1981 and concluded the rural homeownership program `` represents a cost-effective strategy to provide decent shelter to low-income households and to assist them in overcoming the burden of poverty.'' The study, financed with a grant from the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, also found homeownership had indirect benefits, particularly on children, such as stabilizing family life. In 1986, when most borrowers had five years' experience with the program, the study found most were ahead in their payments. Only 7 percent were as much as three months behind, 5 percent had returned their homes to the <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION>, and only 1.3 percent had lost their homes to foreclosure. Poverty-level borrowers were less likely than others to be delinquent and more likely to be ahead in payments, the study showed. At the same time, subsidies to the families declined steadily. `` The decline in the subsidy was in part a reflection of upward economic mobility, and this was most evident among young families with children,'' the study said. The Washington-based council advises low-income and minority groups seeking federal assistance for improving rural housing and studies and makes recommendations for state and local housing policies. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> said the program has been cut from $ 2.9 billion in 1979 to $ 1.1 billion last year. `` If anything, the need has grown,'' he said. He and Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said they are pressing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to expand the program.
