<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign investment in American companies, real estate and other assets has increased dramatically in recent years and is likely to keep climbing through the year 2000, according to a new study. The private study, released Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said direct foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has jumped by more than 215 percent since 1980, while American investment abroad increased by only one-fifth that rate. And the study said the pace of foreign investment is expected to accelerate, with foreign buyouts in 1988 expected to make up as much as 20 percent of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> acquisitions, up from 5 percent in 1987. However, the report said that in absolute terms, foreign investments still account for only 5 percent to 6 percent of total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets. The study said seven nations account for nearly 85 percent of the foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. They are <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, with $ 75 billion in cumulative investments by 1987; the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, $ 47 billion; <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, $ 33 billion; <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, $ 22 billion; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, $ 20 billion; <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, $ 14 billion; and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, $ 10 billion. Other findings include: _ Foreign investors now own 10 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturing base, with majority interest in the concrete and consumer electronics industries and significant portions of machine tools, chemicals and auto parts _ Most foreign outlays in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are to acquire existing businesses rather than to establish new ones _ Jobs of nearly 3 million Americans are dependent on foreign investment, up from just 1.1 million 10 years ago Foreign affiliates account for 7 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturing jobs. _ More than 25 percent of all commercial and industrial loans in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are owed to foreign banks _ More than 12.5 million acres of farm land in 49 states are owned by foreigners, about 1 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> total The study was compiled with data from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and other sources. The institute is a private organization founded in 1987 to act as a forum on economic policy for lawmakers and business, labor and educational leaders.
