<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Democratic-controlled House has given the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration what amounts to a vote of no confidence for its handling of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s network of national parks. The action came Wednesday as the chamber voted 248-130 for Democratic legislation to strip political appointees in the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deparment </ORGANIZATION> of their day-to-day power over the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The vote capped nearly eight years of friction over a variety of parks and federal land-use issues between the Republican administration and Democrats on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The bill faces an uncertain future in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in the waning weeks of the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. And if it reaches President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s desk, it will be vetoed, says Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagomarsino </PERSON>, R-Calif The proposal, sponsored principally by Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Vento </PERSON>, D-Minn., would make the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> director a presidential appointee who would be confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for a five-year term The director now serves at the pleasure of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary and can be removed at any time for any reason. The bill would require a president to show cause before firing a parks director. The legislation would strip the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary and assistant secretaries of any authority over the park service except for its budget, a matter on which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has the final word. The measure also would create a three-member park system review board _ appointed by the president and confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> _ to advise the director and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on how to improve the national parks. <PERSON> Vento </PERSON>, who leveled no criticism against parks director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mott </PERSON>, said the changes are necessary because professionals in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> have been `` supplanted by political decision-making.'' `` The director of the park service has consistently been ordered -LRB- by superiors -RRB- to give political testimony,'' <PERSON> Vento </PERSON> said. `` The director ought to be free to act, but he is undercut and undermined constantly by political appointees.'' He said that political appointees have forced resignations and transfers of park superintendents they did n't like, changed performance ratings for parks personnel and required park officials to obtain clearance for testimony before congressional committees. `` It's time to put a stop to this,'' said <PERSON> Vento </PERSON>, who chairs the Interior national parks and public lands subcommittee. Subcommittee member <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., said that `` political expediency overrules professional judgment This occurs because the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> holds the reins.'' <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> said that the secretary can not serve as the nation's `` chief park ranger'' when his other duties also make him `` the chief miner, chief oil-driller, chief cattle grazer and chief water developer. <PERSON> Lagomarsino </PERSON> said the plan is unconstitutional, `` completely unworkable'' and a `` dangerous precedent'' because it creates a virtually independent entity within a Cabinet department. Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, said that `` this legislation is the worst kind of micromanagement. The country does not need a law creating a new bureaucracy.''
