<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> spends a lot of time puckering up, it's only natural _ after all, whistling's his work. What some professional whistlers do n't find natural, though, is the way Brandon whistles. He inhales, rather than exhales, to produce his tones. `` I also sort of pop the notes off with my tongue a lot of the time to get a more staccato effect than most whistlers use,'' <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> said Wednesday. He does <PERSON> Bach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Handel </PERSON> pieces and jazz improvisation and will perform with the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> Symphony next year. <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON>, 40, won the 10th International Whistle-Off contest in <LOCATION> Carson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, earlier this year and won the championship of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whistlers </ORGANIZATION>' Convention in <LOCATION> Louisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, for a second year in a row. He says he learned his unusual inhalation technique by accident while walking on the street on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s South Side when he was 7 or 8 years old. `` I was whistling, and I inhaled and made a sound I'd never made before,'' he said. For a long time, <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> studied flute at the American Conservatory of Music, but finally realized there were a lot of flute players, and only one master inhale-whistler. So, for the past 10 years, he has made his living strictly by whistling.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> woman's sour experience with import quotas finally turned into a sweet deal, but it was only a coincidence. A convention of cake bakers is coming to town next month and <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Melendy </PERSON> tried to pick up some special sugar, syrup and molasses shipped by two British decorators. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs officials at <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> stopped the pick up, saying sugar imports were over their quotas. `` They're artists,'' Ms. <PERSON> Melendy </PERSON> said of cake decorating experts <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> MacGregor </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Nicolas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sussex </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, who had shipped the supplies in preparation for the Aug. 11-14 convention expected to draw 1,500 cake decorators. `` They use a very fine, extra-refined sugar. They do n't like our sugar. They're just like a sculptor or painter. They prefer using their own equipment.'' Art finally prevailed Wednesday, even though the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> said it was strictly business. The department decided to relax sugar import quotas in a decision unrelated to Ms. <PERSON> Melendy </PERSON>'s dilemma, said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> said officials determined that more sugar could be imported this year without injury to the domestic market. `` It just happened to work out to her advantage that way,'' he said. Ms. <PERSON> Melendy </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>'s Convention and Cake Show, said she was going to move fast retrieving the 88-pound box held since July 19. `` I'm going to run back out there and get my sugar before they change their minds,'' she said Wednesday.
