<HEAD>Drought Eases In Some Areas, But West Still Dry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the most drought-parched areas of the country received a good dousing last week, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said in a generally optimistic assessment of conditions. `` Rainfall for the past week was substantial in the driest areas,'' the weather service said Wednesday in its latest drought advisory. The report said more than one inch of rainfall from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> westward into <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> had fallen and said it has been the most beneficial precipitation since early April. But the report said extreme conditions still prevail in the West, the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>. Some locations received more than eight inches of rain, with a few areas having the equivalent of two months of normal rainfall, the advisory said. The five-day forecast through Aug. 1 calls for some heavy rain across <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and along the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, with widely scattered thundershowers along the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. But the agency said generally hot and dry conditions will spread to the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> regions. Normal rainfall is forecast for the second week in August in the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the Southeast, with near normal or below normal temperatures. But above normal temperatures were predicted for the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Rainfall caused the level of creeks, streams and rivers throughout the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the middle and lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the Northeast to rise temporarily. But streamflows across the rest of the country were still very low, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Hydrological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> division of the agency. Some reservoirs reported increased storage levels, the report said, and water-use restrictions remained in effect in some parts of the country. Temperatures across the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> dropped from three degrees to six degrees below normal, although temperatures remained as much as nine degrees above normal along the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Record high temperatures were still being reported in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, the service said. Extreme dry conditions continued to increase the danger of fire in the far West and the northern plains and the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>, the service added. The report said 12 percent of the country slipped into the extreme drought category between mid-June and mid-July, with about 45 percent of the country affected by July 16. The nation's worst recorded drought was in 1934 when 61 percent of the country was put in the extreme category.
