<HEAD>FDA Approves New Artificial Sweetener</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is allowing use of a no-calorie sweetener as a table sugar substitute and ingredient in some food products. The substance, acesulfame potassium, was developed in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and is used in 20 other countries as an additive in various pharmaceutical products, some baked goods and candies, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. Regulations permitting use of the sweetener, to be marketed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as `` Sunette,'' take effect upon publication in the Federal Register today. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is allowing its use in chewing gum, dry beverage mixes, instant coffee, instant tea, gelatins, puddings and non-dairy creamers. However, the Center for Science in the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION>, a consumer interest group, told the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> it was concerned that the sweetener may have caused tumors found in laboratory animals. But the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said the tumors were `` what could routinely be expected'' and not due to feeding with <PERSON> Sunette </PERSON>. Sunette is a product of the <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Celanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Somerville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The company did not seek <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approval to use Sunette in soft drinks. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> deferred action on the company's request to use the sweetener in candies and other confections in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In the past the agency has interpreted the Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act as barring the use of non-nutritive sweeteners in candies. Sunette is said to be 200 times sweeter than sugar. It joins saccharin, another no-calorie sweetener, and the low-calorie sugar substitute aspartame on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market.
