<HEAD>Train Service Returns To Normal Two Days After Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Their two-day strike broken by the government, hundreds of train crews returned to work today and brought service back to normal, officials of the state-run railroad said. Police said all but a dozen of the 1,463 strikers and their relatives arrested during protests at stations and railway facilities were freed after the strikers agreed to return to work. The remaining 12 jailed employees of the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> face formal charges of neglecting their duty, police said. Engineers and other employees walked off the job Tuesday to demand higher pay and shorter hours. The government said the strike was illegal. The railroad said the strike disrupted about 90 percent of normal daily service of 2,050 trains and affected more than 1 million passengers. The strikers demanded that work hours be reduced from an average 245 hours to 144 hours a month. They also wanted a doubling of their living and other allowances. Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyun-jae </PERSON> said a government offer that the strikers had rejected would take effect, cutting regular monthly work hours to 224 and increasing allowances from the current $ 100 to $ 138 a month. Engineers with 10 years' experience now make about $ 1,200 a month, including allowances.
