<HEAD>Palestinian Leader Calls For Talks With Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent pro-PLO leader from the occupied territories called for direct talks with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> representatives and said he would even speak with hard-line Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>. In a rare dialogue with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> peace activists, <PERSON> Faisal </PERSON> <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION>' `` dream'' is to have <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as well as the occupied lands, but they are willing to compromise and split the land to end the `` nightmares.'' `` As a Palestinian, my problem is with the Israelis _ so I must speak with them,'' <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` So we're willing to speak with <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, not because he is a a man of peace ... but because we know this man was chosen by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to represent them.'' As he spoke, dozens of anti-Arab demonstrators stood outside and protested against the forum, sponsored by the broad-based <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> peace movement, Peace Now. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> is banned in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and the protesters held signs saying, `` Peace Now is a knife in the back.'' The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> refuses to recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, but a recent document drawn up by <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bassam </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharif </PERSON> called for direct talks with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> under the auspices of an international conference. The document was criticized by extremist factions of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON> is a popular figure among residents of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> once called him the leading <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> representative in the areas. He seemed to back <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharif </PERSON>'s policy. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> listeners asked him whether Palestinians will be satisfied with a state alongside <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and not try to conquer the Jewish state itself. `` Indeed, I do have a dream,'' he said. `` But I am not willing to impose my dreams upon my fellow men,'' he said. `` We will have to give up a lot of dreams _ but also a lot of nightmares.'' The statements were greeted with loud applause. <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON>, director of the East Jerusalem-based <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, was released in July from an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> jail, where he had been held without trial for nine months. Before the anti-occupation uprising began Dec. 8, he was involved in clandestine talks with <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Amirav </PERSON>, a former member of the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, which is fiercely opposed to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, kicked <PERSON> Amirav </PERSON> out of the party over the meetings. <PERSON> Amirav </PERSON>, leftist parliamentarian <PERSON> Yair </PERSON> <PERSON> Tzaban </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> journalist <PERSON> Redwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayash </PERSON>, who was also released from jail without trial recently, addressed the unusual gathering with <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON>. It was the first public dialogue between Israelis and Palestinians in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> since the uprising started. <PERSON> Tzaban </PERSON>, of the small socialist <ORGANIZATION> Mapam </ORGANIZATION> party, called o