<HEAD>Sexual Activity by Unmarried Women Increased in 1982-87, Study
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Concern about AIDS has not decreased sexual activity among unmarried women since 1982, but has helped increased their use of condoms, a nationwide survey suggests. Seventy-six percent of unmarried women ages 18 to 44 were sexually active last year compared with 71 percent in 1982, the survey estimates. The study was conducted by <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Darroch </PERSON> <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Alan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guttmacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which studies fertility issues, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fordyce </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Ortho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Raritan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. It appears in the current issue of the institute's publication, `` Family Planning Perspectives.'' The paper says the estimates should be accurate within 2 percentage points, but <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> said that estimates of sexual activity may be low. The researchers compared 1982 and 1987 nationwide surveys commissioned by <ORGANIZATION> Ortho </ORGANIZATION>. The surveys asked a variety of questions about contraception and included married and unmarried women. For 1987, questionnaires were completed by 60 percent of unmarried women who received them, giving data from 2,465 women. Researchers estimated that for unmarried women ages 18 to 44, 15 percent have never had sex and 9 percent have had only infrequent sex, leaving 76 percent considered sexually active, <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> said. The same kind of calculation yielded the 71 percent for 1982, she said. Increases in sexual activity may mean young adults believe they can avoid getting acquired immune deficiency syndrome through sexual contact, that they can judge a person's health by appearance and that they are protecting themselves by choosing only apparently healthy people as partners, researchers said. The study also found that condoms were used by 16 percent of unmarried women ages 18 to 44 and at risk for unintended pregnancy, an increase from 9 percent. Researchers cited publicity about the condom's effectiveness in preventing spread of sexually transmitted diseasese, especially AIDS. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kegeles </PERSON>, a research psychologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said Wednesday she is not surprised by the reported levels of sexual activity. `` I think heterosexuals are just not feeling terribly at risk for AIDS,'' she said. She called the reported increase in condom use `` terrific'' and said the trend must continue. Men and women should feel they can tell a partner they insist on condoms as a routine matter, she said. <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> said despite the condom trend, the 1987 level of use remains low. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tew </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Guttmacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said the study focused on women because `` that's all we have data on.''
