<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said she wo n't see a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and hopes it will never come to pass, and she rejected calls for uniform taxes and a central bank for the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, in a radio interview Wednesday, said officials proposing a federal government for <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> `` spend far too much time talking about these airy-fairy ideas. `` They say ` Let's have European union.' I say ` What do you mean, because I ca n't see any of you dissolving your own countries into a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>','' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said. The 62-year-old prime minister said a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> would `` never come in my lifetime and I hope never at all.'' It was her most outspoken criticism yet of what she regards as impractical overenthusiasm for a European federation. She spoke on the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Jimmy Young Show,'' a mixture of chatty interviews and popular music aimed mainly at housewives. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s Brussels-based executive commission, refused to comment on the interview <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on July 6, predicted that within 10 years 80 percent of social and economic legislation in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </O