<HEAD>Policemen Strike, Three Die in Gujarat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rioters fatally stabbed three people in the western state of <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>, where a police strike entered its fourth day today and prompted officials to call out the army, the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The stabbings occurred Wednesday night in <LOCATION> Godhra </LOCATION>, 465 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, the news agency said. The identities of the victims and the motive behind their slayings were not immediately known. The strike by state police was called after the government on Sunday ordered the arrest of union leaders who were demanding higher wages and better benefits. Officials accused the leaders of inciting a police rebellion. The policemen walked off the job Monday in <LOCATION> Ahmedabad </LOCATION>, an industrial city 18 miles south of <LOCATION> Gandhinagar </LOCATION>, the state capital. The strike later spread all over the state and units of the federal reserve police and other paramilitary forces were ordered to take up routine police duties. Policemen in 138 out of the state's 426 police stations joined in the strike, the sixth by <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION> police in nine years, the government said. The policemen are asking for a monthly $ 75 wage hike. A constable earns about $ 142 a month. At least 83 policemen have so far been dismissed and 23 arrested on charges of indiscipline.
