 the matter. A spokesman, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON>, said Wednesday that <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> may have a statement this week. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> memo has remained secret since it was drafted but is expected to be introduced soon in federal court by government lawyers to help support a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawsuit that seeks the ouster of top Teamsters leaders on grounds of corruption. The lawsuit was filed the day <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> died. An <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> transcript of the electronically monitored meeting held in May 1984 quotes Tronolone as telling <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON> that <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> might be worthy of <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON>'s support for secretary-treasurer, considered the second most powerful position in the union, the Times said. In this meeting and another FBI-monitored meeting in June 1984, <PERSON> Salerno </PERSON> listens to brief talk about <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> but does not indicate he has reached any conclusion or will back anybody for the job, the Times said. <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> eventually selected <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> as secretary-treasuer. The newspaper, citing unidentified sources, said <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> personally cleared that appointment with <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moody </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> official to whom <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> sometimes reported in his role as an informant.
