<HEAD>Government Suspends Plans Requiring Journalists To Register</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today temporarily suspended regulations that would require some journalists to register or face penalties that include imprisonment. The regulations, which were to take effect Sunday, drew heavy criticism from media groups here and abroad that accused the white minority government of making further inroads against press freedom. <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, minister of home affairs, said the registration of journalists `` remains a matter of grave concern for the government,'' but that the regulations had been temporarily suspended for `` practical considerations.'' He said the regulations would be reviewed, but gave no indication when he would make a final decision. The broadly worded strictures say anyone carrying out `` news-agency'' business must register with the government or face a 10-year prison term or a $ 8,500 fine. Lawyers say the definition of a `` news agency'' is so broad that major commerical papers that exchange stories, church and political groups that publish newsletters, and businesses that issue regular press statements on their operations could be included if the government so desired. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest news agency, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, and all major international agencies, including The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, were exempted from the regulations. But local journalists who supply news on a part-time basis to some of the world's major news organizations would be required to register if they work for more than one employer, which many do. Under the regulations, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> would be able to remove journalists from the registration list and prevent those people from working in the profession if he objects to their reporting. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> already has broad censorship powers that allow him to close down publications and expel foreign journalists. The latest regulations appear aimed at the small, local news agencies around the country. But most news organizations operating in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> receive reports from the local agencies and would be affected as well. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has accused the local agencies of endangering public safety by reporting unfavorably on police activities, forced removals of poor blacks and labor disputes in rural areas that are not covered regularly by any other news organizations. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correspondents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has said that even journalists not required to register would be `` compromised'' because they would be seen as having favored status with the government. State-of-emergency regulations already in force restrict reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of detainees, some forms of protest and a broad range of statement the government considers subversive. Under apartheid, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
