<HEAD>Vietnamese-Americans Plan Joint MIA Searches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> appear ready to intensify efforts to search together and account for 1,761 Americans still missing from the Vietnam War, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said today. An embassy statement said experts from both countries meeting over the past four days discussed plans to work `` on concerted efforts within the next three months to make significant progress'' to resolve the divisive issue. The two sides, which met in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, reviewed `` arrangements for joint investigative, survey and excavation activities'' during the period. The statement described the meetings as `` quite productive, and we look forward to greatly expanded cooperation in coming months.'' Members of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team, which returned from <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> today, will discuss implementation of the joint searches in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the statement said. The Vietnam War ended in April 1975 with a communist victory over the U.S.-backed South Vietnamese government. In recent months, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has made significant moves to resolve the MIA issue. It said this month that it would try to resolve 70 `` priority cases'' this year and welcome more joint excavations of warplane crash sites. Facing a ruinous economy and shunned by the non-communist world for its invasion of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has been making efforts at building some bridges to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other western and Asian nations. <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has withdrawn some of its forces from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and participated in the Indonesian-sponsored talks to find a political solution to the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> conflict. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> technical team to the <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> talks was led by Lt. Col. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and was joined by representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Identification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>. Both units are based in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The talks were agreed upon during a meeting at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> June 8 between Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Co </PERSON> <PERSON> Thach </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and retired Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON>, who last August reached an agreement with <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> for an accelerated search for MIAs, especially the 70 on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s priority list. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in turn promised to consider <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s humanitarian problems The priority cases are those the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> considers most easily resolvable because it says the Vietnamese have information on them. These include cases where there are photographs of airmen taken after their capture during the war. Since the <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> agreement, <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has on five occasions turned over to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remains it identified as those of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen killed in the war. The last turnover, involving 25 remains, was on July 13. Since the war ended, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has returned more than 150 sets of remains that the army laboratory confirmed as those of Americans. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> says it has returned the remains of 241 Americans and information on 45 others whose remains were `` determined to be no longer in existence.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has denied charges by some <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> private citizens that it is holding live Americans as prisoners.
</TEXT>
