<HEAD>Taiwan Proposes Mainland Chinese Visits To Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government official said today that proposed legislation would allow people from mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to visit <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> for two months if their relatives here are gravely ill or die. <PERSON> Director </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuan-jen </PERSON>, director of the Exit and <ORGANIZATION> Entry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, said the proposal would be submitted soon to the Cabinet for consideration. Under the plan, mainland Chinese would be allowed to visit their spouses, parents and children if their relatives in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> can present documents to prove illness or death in the family, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said. The Nationalists have maintained no official contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communists </ORGANIZATION> since 1949 after losing a civil war on the mainland. They eased a ban last year to allow Taiwanese to visit <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for family reunions.
