<HEAD>University Closed Following Student Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities closed one of the nation's six universities indefinitely following violent clashes between rival student political groups, police said today At least 10 students at <ORGANIZATION> Rajshahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> were injured Wednesday in the clashes and nearly 100 dormitory rooms were ransacked, police said. The students also set fire to furniture and books, they said. The trouble erupted when more than 100 supporters of the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Jamaat-e-Islami </ORGANIZATION> party raided the campus and clashed with supporters of an eight-party alliance led by the country's main opposition leader, Sheikh <PERSON> Hasina </PERSON>, a district official said The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the <ORGANIZATION> Jamaat </ORGANIZATION> supporters were armed with iron rods, sticks and knives. Three students were hospitalized, he said. One was reported in critical condition. `` We have closed the university for the safety and security of the students and the campus,'' <PERSON> Amanullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, university vice chancellor, said by telephone. Examinations scheduled for next month were postponed. The university at <LOCATION> Rajshahi </LOCATION>, 168 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, has more than 11,000 students. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>'s universities often are sites of political unrest. Opposition parties have been agitating since November to oust President <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershad </PERSON>, a former army general who seized power in a coup in 1982.
