<HEAD>Boston University To Help Manage Troubled School System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHELSEA, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' most impoverished school system will be managed by <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> under a plan officials say could help `` redirect education in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Under the plan approved Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chelsea </LOCATION>, a blue-collar city of 26,000 north of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> will serve as an unpaid consultant for about six months. If the plan works out, the university will manage the schools for a decade. `` We see it as the place to begin educational reform,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` We hope <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> will bring the cutting edge of educational technology to <LOCATION> Chelsea </LOCATION>. We have all the problems of a large urban center but we're small enough so the effects will be measureable.'' <PERSON> Chelsea </PERSON> school officials say the city is the poorest in the state in per capita income. The school system has low reading test scores and one of the highest teen-age pregnancy rates in the state. <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> wrote a 300-page report outlining a 10-year plan to reduce dropout rates and improve teaching in the 3,300-student system. `` We could be model for the country,'' said <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>, a director of the program. `` It's perfect for the national reform movement _ we're stressing a lot of teacher and parental involvement. If other universities want to do this, they can come to us and see the results. We're putting our reputation on the line with this.'' The university plans to review the curriculum, attempt to raise teacher salaries and focus heavily on early childhood education, <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> said. He estimated the annual cost of the plan at $ 2 million and said <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> will seek federal grants and corporate sponsors. University faculty and staff will advise the school administration on `` everything from appointments and curricula to school buses,'' said <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, who conceived the plan. `` This is the first step to redirect education in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said.
