<HEAD>Red Cross Cited For Errors At Blood Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> laboratory at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> says it has closed for reorganization after being cited by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for more than 150 errors, mostly involving AIDS and hepatitis screening. The faults were detected between January 1987 and June 1988, <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON>, chief operating officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bi-State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chapter </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday. He said 152 blood donations collected during the 18-month period required further investigation and of that total, 96 donors were re-evaluated for AIDS or hepatitis. `` All 96 re-tested negative to initial screening tests, and medical history evaluations determined that none were involved in high-risk activities,'' he said. But he said five showed `` indeterminant'' results. These donors, and the six patients who received their blood products, will be monitored for the next few months to determine any health hazards, <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> said. He said the donors and patients involved had been contacted. Other FDA citations involved faults in computer systems, administrative systems and records. <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> said the mistakes were mostly a result of human error and said disciplinary measures have been taken. `` With the help of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> we have made appropriate corrections,'' he said. `` To protect the health of patients who rely on <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> blood, we are committed to a standard of zero errors.'' <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> will temporarily transfer its lab work to a private laboratory in <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and a quality control office will be established under the direction of a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> vice president. The Missouri-Illinois region is one of 56 regional blood service operations in the country. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> supplies half of the nation's need for blood and blood products, <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> said. Each year more than 4 million volunteers donate over 6 million units of blood to more than 1.5 million patients, he said.
