ON> Colliers </ORGANIZATION> three years to decide whether to exercise an option on the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> property. If they did, other developers would have 90 days to submit bids, which the <ORGANIZATION> Colliers </ORGANIZATION> would be allowed to top. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> argued that this procedure favors the <ORGANIZATION> Colliers </ORGANIZATION> because competitors would not be able to come up with the development plans and financing within a short time. They tried to convince the House to send the bill back to the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> with instructions to revise it to include an open competitive bidding process. Their recommittal motion lost 279-133. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the Indian Affairs and Energy and Natural Resources committees took testimony on the issue on Monday but have not drafted legislation of their own. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> property is in <LOCATION> Collier </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. The bulk of the 108,000 acres lies immediately north of the Big Cypress National Preserve, which borders Everglades National Park on the park's northwest side. Another parcel, of 5,000 acres, is adjacent to the Fakahatchee Strand State Preserve, known home to perhaps a fifth of the 30 to 50 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> panthers believed left in the wilderness. The state preserve is west of the national preserve. And 19,620 acres is next to the state's <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Romano-Ten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thousand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> Aquatic Preserve, on the Gulf coast south of <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION> and west of <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
