 Abortion-rights advocates hailed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s lopsided vote to extend Medicaid funding to abortions for rape and incest victims as a breakthrough, but the plan still faces skepticism in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and hostility from the White House The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s 73-19 vote Wednesday marked the first departure by either chamber from the restrictive abortion policies of the past seven years. Current law, in effect since 1981, limits payments to abortions in which the life of the mother is endangered. Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, R-Conn., sponsor of the expansion, said the vote Wednesday represented `` a clear change'' from recent tradition `` What is terribly important is just to break that chain'' of restrictive regulations, he said. `` It's a first small start.'' The abortion provision was part of a $ 140 billion appropriations bill passed 80-16 Wednesday evening after a day of frenzied votes and shifting tactics on abortion, family planning and AIDS issues. The bill will keep the departments of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, and Education in business during fiscal 1989 beginning Oct. 1. Its highlights include $ 7.1 billion for employment and training; $ 1.2 billion for AIDS research, treatment, prevention and education, and $ 4.2 billion for tutoring and other services to disadvantaged students. In a June 28 statement, the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> urged the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to strike its Medicaid abortion provision, saying it `` diverges from longstanding policy on this issue. ... The president's senior advisers would recommend that he veto this bill, solely based on the inclusion of this language provision.'' The abortion provision adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is more restrictive than the simple extension <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> sponsored during the committee process. Federal money would only be available in promptly reported rape or incest cases, and states could retain the existing, more limited eligibility if they so desire. Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., sponsor of the modified version, said it reflects `` the middle ground'' on a difficult issue <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> said it had a better shot at surviving negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members, who did not include a Medicaid expansion in their version of the appropriations bill. Asked about the possibility of a veto, <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> replied, `` Considering everything else that's in the bill and that it's an election year, it could be overridden.'' But <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, legislative director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> To </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he was confident the final product would not contain the Medicaid abortion expansion. `` The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is strongly committed to the current law. So is the president,'' said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. In any case, he said, his group considers the <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> amendment `` a very good outcome'' because it gives states some leeway and eliminates the possibility of rape claims six months into a pregnancy. There was little controversy over money allocations in the bill, which was drawn up in accordance with the budget framework agreed to last year by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. But there were enough AIDS, abortion and family planning amendments to prolong debate for three days. In a confusing series of events, senators three times rejected attempts by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> to renew an expiring ban on federal funds for AIDS education materials that promote or encourage homosexuality. Instead they adopted an amendment described by its sponsor, Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., as a pre-emptive strike against the <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> ban While it bans federal funds for materials that directly promote or encourage homosexuality, at the same time it says the materials must provide accurate information on how to avoid getting and transmitting AIDS. Some senators disavowed their votes last year in favor of the <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> restrictions, saying they wrongly believed the restrictions were toothless. `` It is a fact that effective materials have been shelved and vital proposals have been tabled because of the fear of what this amendment might do,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Nevertheless, after embracing the <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> amendment 61-37, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> later passed another amendment _ this one containing the <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> restrictions as well as a phrase saying federally funded AIDS materials can not `` use words stating that homosexuality is ` normal,' ` natural' or ` healthy.''' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 48-45 to kill a <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> amendment banning federal money to school-based clinics that distribute contraceptives or provide abortion counseling or referral services. Later lawmakers by voice vote approved a more limited version of the same amendment, one which dropped the contraceptives section but retained the ban relating to abortion services. School-based clinics are set up by local school boards to provide health services that sometimes include family planning. Some receive Medicaid funds and money from block grants funneled through states. Voting against the abortion proposal were Sens. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Ky., <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, D-Ala., <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, R-Ky., <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, D-Nev., <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich., <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON>, D-Ala., <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Daschle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.D. </LOCATION>, Wyche <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, D-Ga., <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERS