<TEXT>
 A town north of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> was under curfew today after mobs destroyed Moslem-owned tea shops and attacked police with stones and catapults, leaving one person dead and five wounded, sources said. It was not certain whether the violence was related to this week's national leadership changes in which hard-line former army general <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> assumed the positions of president and head of the only political party. Also today, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> urged <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s leaders to investigate alleged brutality by authorities who quelled riots in which scores of people died. The government said 43 people died in March unrest, including 41 who suffocated in a packed police van as they were being driven to prison. Unofficial reports put the death toll at more than 100. `` These investigations should lead to the bringing to justice of those responsible for human rights violations,'' the London-based human rights organization said in response to a query by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The government news agency said Wednesday that the curfew was imposed and all demonstrations banned Tuesday in <LOCATION> Myede </LOCATION>, 220 miles north of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, after rioters attacked police with catapults and stones. The official <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> said police had to shoot to disperse the crowd and order was restored after several hundred rioters destroyed two tea shops and a third building. The mob first set upon the Moslem-owned tea shops and then went on a looting spree, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. The sources believed the incident was a spillover of riots in nearby Prome. Prome has been under martial law since July 22, after six days of mob violence that re