<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s foreign minister today allayed concerns that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was reneging on its pledge to withdraw the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` This impression has just been dispelled,'' <PERSON> Sahabzada </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said after a meeting with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. `` Our position and that of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in regard to the withdrawal is no longer divergent.'' The pace of the pullout and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hopes for fair elections in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> were topics for discussion during the foreign minister's visit There are an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Half are supposed to be withdrawn by Aug. 15. Pakistani President <PERSON> Mohamnad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Haq </PERSON> raised concerns last week that the Soviets were replenishing them with new troops. But <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said `` the Soviets are carrying out the withdrawal.'' Through <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> armed Afghan rebels fighting the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and the pro-Soviet government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said this week that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> had sent new assurances that the Soviets would fulfill their commitment in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords of last May to withdraw half the troops by Aug. 15. The report that they would be replaced was traced to the Soviet military commander in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, who apparently did not have the backing of his superiors in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> are comparing notes on how to monitor the Soviet withdrawal _ and on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s future after the troops are gone. One question is whether the rebels then would be able to bring down President <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON>. Another is the kind of government that would follow. Several of the rebel leaders would like to install a fundamentalist Moslem regime akin to the government in neighboring <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. `` It is extremely important we look beyond <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and continue close cooperation with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the interest of peace and security in the region,'' <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has close ties to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which gave refuge to millions of Afghan refugees besides funneling covert <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support to the rebels. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are hoping the elections <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> has set for Nov. 16 will be fair, but there is a question how much pressure <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> might try to apply. `` We will stress that elections should be free and fair, but it is not up to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to prescribe how they should be held,'' said an official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> dismissed his civilian government in May, but did not call for elections within the 90 days prescribed by the Pakistani constitution. He also barred candidates from running with party labels. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> took the position that party-based elections could mislead the voters. Critics say this will focus attention on local issues and work against <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s main national opposition, the <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> It is headed by <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, whose father was ousted in 1977 in a coup led by <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> and executed. On another touchy issue, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> must certify in October that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> does not possess a nuclear explosive device in order for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to continue. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will see <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> briefly on Friday. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration last year fought off a drive in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to shelve <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> amid indications the country was trying to develop a nuclear bomb. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has denied making such an attempt. It is receiving $ 260 million in military aid this year and $ 380 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic assistance.
