<HEAD>With PM-Forest Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with additional comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interior Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>, just back from touring fire-scorched <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, said today firefighters are now fighting all new outbreaks. But one official said it's still possible that some new fires might be left to burn. `` Yellowstone is not in danger. ... We're not going to let <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> be damaged by this,'' <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America'' program. Fighting all new outbreaks has always been a possibility in the usual `` let it burn'' policy of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, Chief <PERSON> Ranger </PERSON> <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> said afterward. Both <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> and the secretary defended the post-1972 policy of fighting only fires that threaten developed areas or that could spread out of the park into timbering operations on adjacent <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> lands. The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> follow similar policies in their wildnerness areas because fires are important in generating healthy ecosystems. `` The fact is that <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> has about 3 percent currently burning. ... But they've had a sufficient area under their fire-management plan that their policy now is to fight new fires that break out,'' <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> said in an interview the secretary was right in his facts, and all recent outbreaks had been attacked with a view of keeping the fires small, but the policy was unchanged _ decisions will be made case by case, and the action taken will depend on where the fire is and what is threatened, how many firefighters are available and how dangerous it would be to commit them. A few firefighters can knock down a small blaze that might be impossible to control if left alone, he noted. Any fire that breaks out in remote areas might well be left alone now, he said. Any fire near the park boundaries probably would be attacked. Crews have begun using flame throwers to start backfires against fires that have so far scorched some 109,000 of the park's 2.2 million acres. The fires had moved to within six miles of Old Faithful and forced the closing of one of the park's main entrances. `` In <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> specifically we're fighting probably six or eight large fire areas right now,'' <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> flew over some of the damaged forest land Wednesday and voiced confidence afterwards in the policy of allowing remote areas to burn. In his comments today, the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary said the flames had gone far enough. `` What they tell me is we've got standing timber that is as dry or drier than kiln-dried lumber. That makes it just take off like crazy when you have a fire,'' he said. `` In these conditions there's very little control we can have over these fires.'' <PERSON> Dabney </PERSON> said the damage could even help naturalists learn more about the forest by providing a close look at how large-scale fires clear old brush for new wildlife habitat. `` What we're looking at probably occurred naturally in the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> area every 200 to 400 years,'' he said. `` We've never really had the chance to see wildfire on this scale in the Yellowstone ecosystem, so we're going to look at it very closely from a research standpoint and know a lot more specifically about the benefits of what's going on there now.'' About 80 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> is lodgepole pine in a `` fire-dependent ecology,'' he said. Natural fires `` Are very important to keep species diversified. Many wildlife species will leave an area that's too thick and stagnant.'' New trees and a wealth of wildlife-attracting vegetation grow in the open areas created by fires, whose ashes act as a natural fertilizer, he said.
