<HEAD>U.S. Discloses Production Sites of Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate to the Conference on Disarmament today declared the location of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' chemical weapons production facilities. Delegate <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> said he hoped the declaration would `` contribute both to greater confidence and to the negotiation of related provisions'' of a convention banning the production, stockpiling and use of chemical weapons. The <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> conference has been negotiating such a convention for 20 years. This year's summer session began July 7. `` The declaration we are making today is unprecedented,'' <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> told the 40-nation conference. `` We urge other countries that possess chemical weapons production facilities to declare the locations of their facilities and to outline how the facilities would be destroyed,'' he said. He said no other conference member had provided information on chemical weapons production facilities. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are the only two members of the conference who have acknowledged possessing chemical weapons. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has said it believes about 15 nations possess such weapons, but it has refused to name them. The production facilities declared by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Pine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bluff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>; Muscle Shoals in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ammunition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> Proving Ground in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has declared the amount of its stockpiles, but not their location nor the location of production sites. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> said in December that its chemical weapons stocks total 50,000 tons, but Western experts have estimated that the actual total is much higher. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also submitted to the conference ideas for ways to destroy chemical weapons under an eventual ban. Delegates have drafted many parts of a chemical weapons ban. The main unresolved issue is how to guard against cheating.
