<HEAD>Givenchy Shows Sexy Luxury As Couture Showings Wind Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sexy luxury at <ORGANIZATION> Givenchy </ORGANIZATION> and casual luxury at Per Spook were the keynotes of fashion Thursday, winding up the couture showings for winter. Following Spook's show, a committee of 24 international fashion writers awarded this season's Golden Thimble prize for all-around excellence to Dior's couturier, <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Bohan </PERSON>. Many of the designers came to the Palais Galliera fashion museum with a few models wearing their designs, to participate in the Golden Thimble ceremonies. `` Dior's mink-trimmed taupe suits actually made me jealous,'' said couturier <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Feraud </PERSON>, a top-rated designer himself. `` They were perfectly cut and made.'' <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON>'s suits shown in the morning were also perfectly tailored, with nipped waists, most narrow skirts short to an inch or two above the knee. <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON> has been an advocate of short skirts, but also showed some longer lengths. There were bursts of color, even in the fabulous furs that went with the dresses and suits. <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, mink and sable were dyed ruby, violet, pastel blue and yellow to go with outfits in different dazzling tones. Cloth coats were usually luxurious cashmere, of course. One model looked great in lavender with a dark purple windowpane plaid. Bicolored suede and satin outfits were other appealing highlights _ royal blue or amethyst with a rust belt and toque, for instance. There were a few pants for daytime or evening, more often than not dressed up with neat matador boleros and Spanish grandee hats. <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON>'s late-day wear was more siren-bright than usual, though a few black beaded and sequined numbers cropped up. More frequent were the satin dresses with sashes in tones like pink and raspberry or emerald and magenta. Feathers, beehive-ruffled sleeves, black velvet appliques on bicolored stretch jersey dresses added up to coquettish looks. <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON> lenghthened a few hemlines to mid-calf, though the dressy strapless-topped models were usually clinging to the torso, flared below the knee. <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON>'s funny hats were remarkable, too. Besides boaters, there were ripple or wave shapes, lace-edged tiny cones or jigsaw-puzzle shapes, big fur rims on wide-brimmed hats. Ball gowns were sumptuous as always, whether slim and with plunging decolletes or strapless with full taffeta skirts, some with an iridescent effect. Per Spook chose some short styles _ minis and full shorts, even though they were for the fall _ or much longer skirts and pants. As usual, the Norwegian-born designer presented color-coordinated groups of clothes from day to evening, all walking out at once, an appealing way of showing a modestly winning collection. Combinations of champagne and ivory, royal blue and gray, raspberry and green and sunny yellow and brown were lively rather than loud. A soft mohair boxy coat topped a full chocolate brown cashmere skirt, the smocked silk crepe blouse echoing the tones of the outfit. There was plenty of luxury in this charming collection that featured details such as sequined bodices over full leather skirts, fitted and piped tweed military jackets, double-flounced clinging suede dresses, excellent flannel pants with embroidered bolero jackets, intricate seaming on bodices and hems of evening dresses. Spook's strapless ballerina-length gowns and the tiered silk dresses in white and pink ribbons looked great for young debs or sweethearts of Sigma Chi. These final adorable dresses were appropriately called `` La Vie en Rose.''
