<SECOND>AM-China-Prices,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Soar In China For Brand Name Cigarettes, Spirits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government raised the base prices of its best cigarettes and liquors Thursday in an effort to break up a thriving black market, and it allowed state-run stores to set the retail prices for the first time. Store managers said that on Friday they will raise the prices even higher. The cost of a pack of a popular brand of cigarettes went up nearly 400 percent, and the price of a fifth of a bottle of spirits shot up 750 percent. But consumers were used to paying at least that much anyway. The black market holds a virtual monopoly on top-quality cigarettes and liquor in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Private sellers bribe store managers to sell them the goods wholesale and then resell them to the public at inflated prices. On Thursday, brand-name cigarettes and liquors surfaced in stores for the first time in about 15 years. Business was brisk. At the Xidan Market in west <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, manager <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Dajiang </PERSON> said he sold 1,500 cartons of cigarettes in two hours during the morning. `` We could have sold more, but we're saving them for tomorrow to see what price they'll fetch,'' he said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the world's largest producer and consumer of tobacco, has 300 million smokers. Across town at the <LOCATION> Guandong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Market </LOCATION>, manager <PERSON> Zhen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciping </PERSON> said wines and cigarettes had been selling fast. `` Today we're experimenting, seeing which brands the masses like,'' she said. `` Tomorrow we'll raise the prices of the popular ones.'' Customers complained the prices were too high, but they bought anyway. `` The prices are the same as you can get from the private sellers and that's too high,'' said customer <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhiping </PERSON>, holding four cartons of popular <PERSON> Zhonghua </PERSON> cigarettes at the Xidan Market. The cigarettes went up almost 400 percent from 49 cents to $ 1.90 a pack. Thursday's price increases mainly affected 13 name-brand cigarettes and 13 famous-brand spirits, although the costs of some B-grade items also jumped. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is experiencing its highest inflation since 1949. Consumer prices last month were 19 percent higher than in June 1987. Last year, the previous high, inflation hit 7.2 percent. In May, the government raised the prices of vegetables, pork, sugar and eggs as part of a far-reaching economic reform program to end state controls of prices. Economists hope to increase production and raise the standard of living. In announcing the increases Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, or Cabinet, said it would let the price of the 26 brands be determined by the market. Managers in state-run stores said that meant they could set prices and reap a profit from their sales, something unheard of a few years ago. According to the managers, the government set a base price. If a store is able to sell the items for more, it can keep the difference. At <LOCATION> Guandong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Market </LOCATION>, manager <PERSON> Zhen </PERSON> said she planned to let the workers share the profit. At <LOCATION> Xidan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> said it would be invested in the store. Managers said Thursday they would have no problem selling some items for a profit. `` We're not even selling <LOCATION> Maotai </LOCATION> yet,'' Ms. <PERSON> Zhen </PERSON> said, referring to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s popular sorghum liquor whose base price rose 750 percent Thursday from $ 5.40 to $ 40.50 for a fifth of a gallon. `` We're waiting to see what the market will bear. But several problems were immediately apparent with the government's plan to price the profiteers out of business. Only a few stores had the name-brand goods, and they had enough for just a few days. Also, prices in the state-run stores still were generally below those of the black market. Store managers said they expected profiteers to continue to buy large quantities of cigarettes and liquor at the state-run stores. `` Then they'll turn around and make a profit on our goods once we run out,'' a shop manager said. `` This problem wo n't be solved in a flash.''
</TEXT>
