<HEAD>Office Writes Bogus Tickets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A city patrolman with a heart says he has been writing one or two bogus traffic tickets a week in the names of non-existent motorists for about 18 months. `` I just could not bring myself to write tickets,'' said Patrolman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON>. `` I started seeing the human beings behind the drivers' wheels.'' <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON>, 36, a 17-year veteran, has been suspended for 25 days. Police Chief <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> concluded that <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> wrote fictitious tickets to maintain `` high enforcement statistics.'' Chief Jefferson District Judge <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Smalley </PERSON> said this week that a computer listing of all the tickets <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> has written since 1981 shows that more than 1,000 are in the names of people for whom state transportation employees could not find <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> driver's licenses `` We have to assume that almost all of them are fictitious,'' <PERSON> Smalley </PERSON> said. However, the official letter from <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> to Safety Director <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuster </PERSON> recommending <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON>'s suspension says only what <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> has admitted _ that he wrote one or two phony tickets per week over a year and a half. <PERSON> Kuster </PERSON> said Wednesday that he was unaware that more than 1,000 questionable tickets had been written. And Lt. Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> said the police internal affairs unit's investigation of <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> would be reopened because of that information Each person who gets a traffic ticket is sent a letter by <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> notifying him of his court date. If the person fails to show up, a second letter is sent. If two court appearances are missed, the court sends the ticket to the state <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. That agency sends the ticketed driver a letter warning he will lose his license if the ticket is n't resolved within 20 days, said cabinet spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON>. This year, for the first time, the cabinet began sending tickets that do n't match driver's licenses back to <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Smalley </PERSON> said. In a batch of about 50 returned by the state in March, clerks discovered that <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> had written 29, police Maj. <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rausch </PERSON> then asked them to do a more extensive check, <PERSON> Smalley </PERSON> said. Checking tickets that <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> wrote since 1981 for people whose names began with the letters A through C, the clerks found about 250 for which the state had been unable to locate drivers' licenses, <PERSON> Smalley </PERSON> said He said the clerks made another check of tickets that <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> had written that were never resolved and found 1,050. <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> said he admitted writing the fictitious tickets when called to <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON>'s office a few weeks ago. He said he also wrote legitimate tickets. In his letter, <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> said he considered recommending that <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> be fired, but decided to be more lenient because <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> was not motivated by greed. For example, he did not receive special pay given to officers for court appearances. `` Rather, Officer <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> seems to have been motivated by a self-imposed peer pressure to maintain high enforcement statistics,'' <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> wrote. Assistant City Law Director <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Guagliardo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> may have violated state law. However, <PERSON> Guagliardo </PERSON> said he never determined which statute <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> could have violated because <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> officials told <PERSON> Dotson </PERSON> they did n't wish to prosecute. Since January, <PERSON> Ghrist </PERSON> has been assigned to drive a vehicle that cruises expressways to help stranded motorists.
