<FIRST>r a AM-StickyStamps Bjt   07-28 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sticky Stamps, Bjt,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Service Seeks `Seat Belt' for Stamps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN W. CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service began a 16-month, $ 700,000 quest Thursday to lick the problem of stamps that do n't stay stuck, urging industry to produce an adhesive to serve as a `` seat belt for a stamp. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morison </PERSON>, a senior assistant postmaster general, made it clear during a daylong conference at <ORGANIZATION> Battelle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> that the post office was serious about development of a superior, water-activated adhesive. `` Unfortunately, the news that we have made in the last few days is that we're spending a lot of money on something the press perceives as insignificant,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> told about 100 adhesive industry executives and technical experts. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> would spend nearly $ 90 million this year for stamps, sales of which would generate about $ 8 billion. `` I do n't believe there is a private company, including those that publish newspapers or sell their wares over the airwaves, that would hesitate to invest $ 700,000 to lower the cost of their product while making it perform better. That is exactly what we are doing,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. `` We take it seriously because we know how important that stamp is to every American consumer,'' he told reporters during a break in the conference. `` We really believe that we have to have a stamp that operates very well.'' Adhesive now used by stamp manufacturers performs well when mail is sorted manually or mechanically. But the arrival of high-speed, automated processing, in which stamps are coated with a compound that activates processing equipment, has generated a need for a stronger adhesive that will keep a stamp on an envelope. `` The mail is moving very quickly through our system. In doing that, you are again putting a great deal of stress on the stamp,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. He compared it to a speeding car running into a brick wall, sending a passenger without a seat belt into the windshield. `` You have the same thing in sorting mail. The letter is moving down the processing stream, and all of a sudden it stops. As soon as it stops, it's that same kind of force as the car hitting the brick wall,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said. `` What we are doing is developing an adhesive that will serve as a seat belt for a stamp.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has heard from customers whose letters were destroyed or returned because the stamps fell off, he said. `` The problem ... has n't reached major proportions. But it is clear that it will as the speed of mail processing continues to increase as it must. The time to act is now, and we are turning to the adhesive industry for help,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> told the conference. Dr. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> McGinniss </PERSON>, the program project manager at <LOCATION> Battelle </LOCATION>, said industries will develop potential new adhesives and supply samples to the institute for extensive testing and evaluation. `` Ultimately, we will print real stamps that ... we will put into the mail stream. We'll take them back out, find out if they stuck, and if they stayed on then do the evaluations, a lot more testing,'' <PERSON> McGinniss </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> Battelle </PERSON>, a not-for-profit, multinational research and development organization, will write adhesive specifications which the postal service can use in buying the product from suppliers. Although the research should produce stickier stamps, no change in taste is anticipated. `` Taste is a very personal thing. What we've always sought in taste, and where we think we are, is neutral and bland. And we'd like to stay neutral and bland,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> said `` Taste is in the tongue of the users, and this contract really has nothing to do with that.''
</TEXT>
