<FIRST>u a AM-LandingShuttles Bjt   07-28 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landing Shuttles, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Gets White Sands Space Harbor Ready For Shuttle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Astronauts flying a jet modified to act like a space shuttle make steep 19-degree dives toward the desert floor Mondays through Fridays, flashing at 230 mph 20 feet above a runway of packed, white gypsum. Each time, they have to deal with a malfunctioning computer, broken landing gear, a non-working radio or some other problem generated by a sophisticated computer aboard the Grumman Gulfstream II jet. In addition to all their other shuttle training, astronauts also must practice for a possible landing at the alternative runway in the desert at <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sands </LOCATION>. `` It would be terrible if you had a good mission and messed it up with a bad landing,'' said <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Paczynski </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s project manager at White Sands Space Harbor. Shuttle commanders <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauck </PERSON> and shuttle pilot <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Covey </PERSON> practiced landings Wednesday in the modified jet. `` There's a humongous computer on board that takes the flight characteristics of the shuttle and the flight characteristics of the airplane and matches them together,'' <PERSON> Paczynski </PERSON> said. The computer can simulate a shuttle bringing back a heavy payload, or a stiff wind, or a system malfunction or a combination of problems. <PERSON> Hauck </PERSON> and <PERSON> Covey </PERSON> are scheduled to go up on the next shuttle flight, aboard Discovery, in September or October. A simulated countdown leading to a test firing of the shuttle's main engines ran into a snag Wednesday and was delayed 24 hours <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> engineers hope to fix a small gas leak in a vent line associated with a steering engine without taking Discovery off the pad and into a hangar, a move that could delay the launch as much as two months. The shuttle's primary landing site is <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, a dry lake bed with plenty of room to make up for a less-than-perfect landing. But if it rains at <LOCATION> Edwards </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hauck </PERSON> and <PERSON> Covey </PERSON> could end up gliding down to one of the two dazzlingly white, criss-cross runways at the White Sands dry lake bed. If they land at White Sands, on a dry lake bed between the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> and White Sands National Monument, they will use a runway that has been leveled out a little better since <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lousma </PERSON> landed the shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> there on March 30, 1982. Engineers used lasers to check the smoothness of the runways, <PERSON> Paczynski </PERSON> said Wednesday as he led reporters on a tour of the 100-square-mile complex in the middle of White Sands Missile Range. They also leveled and flattened the surface 300 feet wide on either side of the 300-foot-wide landing strip, in effect making the runway 900 feet wide. At 35,000 feet long, the landing strips are about three times as long as those at commercial airports. July, August and September are the rainy months at <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sands </LOCATION>, when half of the annual 12 inches of rain falls. The `` dry'' lake bed was decidedly wet Wednesday because three-quarters of an inch of rain had fallen the night before, but it was still firm. `` Notice how the bus wo n't get bogged down when it comes to this wet spot,'' <PERSON> Paczynski </PERSON> told reporters as their bus approached a 50-yard-long puddle. `` There's a very hard mantle here 2 inches under the topsoil. That's why you could land an orbiter here even if -LRB- the strip -RRB- were underwater. They would n't, but they could.'' When the shuttle lands on the gypsum flats, it's as if it were landing on a mile-thick, 7-mile-long piece of Sheetrock, the panels used for interior walls. Prevailing southwesterly wind carries gypsum crystals from the lake bed to the famous dunes shimmering in the distance. The wind and the sharp gypsum crystals created havoc the one time a shuttle landed here. The de-service and mating area, where the astronauts disembark and where the shuttle is hoisted aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 for the flight back to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, was so dusty that officials feared for the vessel's safety. So they've moved the area to a less dusty spot in the lee of the mountains, <PERSON> Paczynski </PERSON> said.
