<HEAD>Pentagon Defends Prescription Stimulants For Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pentagon officials on Thursday defended the use of prescribed stimulants to <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilots on long solo flights and said no recent crash has been linked to drug use. `` None of the crashes in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> was linked to drug use,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. `` No crashes anywhere have been related to drug use.'' A West German television network reported Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilots there take Dexedrine to stay alert in flight and take the sedative Seconal to sleep afterwards. Concern has grown in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> following the crashes of five F-16 jet fighters in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> within three months this year. The West German network <ORGANIZATION> ARD </ORGANIZATION> quoted an unidentified <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officer as saying that pilots take Dexedrine `` so that they are able to fly when they have n't gotten enough sleep or do n't feel fit enough.'' Consumer advocate <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> of Public Citizen, appearing on the <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION> program `` Good Morning America, said his group was concerned about `` a military that has to depend upon using uppers and downers to perform well.'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said if commercial pilots used such drugs they would be fired or grounded. `` Imagine the scenario of a fighter pilot flying one of these planes having an hallucination and pressing the wrong button, particularly if there is a bomb on board,'' he said. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> and other officials said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military pilots use such stimulants on long flights across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and Pacific Oceans, and not on exercises over populated areas. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> does not routinely prescribe medication to air crew members, but on long flights where pilot fatigue could present a significant safety risk, stimulant and sedative medications may be authorized by the major command surgeon general,'' said <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. `` Dispensing of these medications is rigidly controlled. Routine use of these medications is never advised. The individual crew member makes the decision to take or not to take the medication,'' he said. Such use, he said, was confined almost exclusively to `` long flights. Dexedrine, Seconal and Temazepam -LRB- a stimulant -RRB- are prescribed almost exclusively for transoceanic solo missions in single-seat aircraft.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> was not considering any changes in the practice, which has been standard for as long as 30 years, spokesmen said. None of the other services, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, prescribe such drugs for pilots, <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said. And the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> issued a statement saying that it neither prescribed nor permitted the use of such drugs on flights by <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilots. `` The missions and environments in which <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilots fly are different,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> statement said. `` <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> pilots seldom fly long, uninterrupted flights in single or two-seater aircraft which <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilots do regularly in deploying aircraft across the ocean on training exercises.'' `` As a matter of policy, naval aviators are not given prescription stimulants or depressants for use during or after flight,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> statement said. `` Only caffeine in the form of coffee and triptophan in the form of warm milk are permitted for these purposes,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> statement said. Col. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consultants </ORGANIZATION> Division of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> surgeon general's office, said in an interview on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION> that the service does `` on occasion prescribe medication to our pilots, but these are under very special circumstances. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said he did not know how often the drugs are taken but said they have been used for `` 25 to 30 years, probably longer.''
