<HEAD>Administration, Key Democrats Oppose U.S., Vietnamese Relations
Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and key <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats on Thursday voiced opposition to any move at this time to establish <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Vietnamese diplomatic interest sections in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. But administration officials held out the promise of full diplomatic relations between the two former adversaries if Vietnamese troops are withdrawn from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Principal support for establishing diplomatic interest sections in the two capitals came from a pair of Republicans, including Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, who spent years as a war prisoner during the Vietnamese war. `` It is a modest step,'' <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. `` It's sole purpose is to speed progress in a number of issues, including Americans missing in action, emigration of Amerasians through the orderly departure program, the release of Vietnamese in re-education camps and the continued Vietnamese occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridge </PERSON>, R-Pa., contended the time is ripe for such a step because the Vietnamese have made it clear they will leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, because the <LOCATION> Vietnamese </LOCATION> economy is shattered, because a new generation is taking power in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>, and because an opportunity exists to woo the Vietnamese away from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> `` Senator <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> and I agreed that the status quo was horribly unacceptable and unsatisfactory,'' <PERSON> Ridge </PERSON> said. `` The parents of our MIA's still wait for word on their missing heroes.'' An interest section is the lowest type of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic contact with another nation and does not involve the establishment of formal diplomatic relations of any kind. Officials of the two nations involved generally use office space in an embassy of a third nation. <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for East Asian and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> affairs, said the administration believes that establishing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Vietnamese interest sections now would harm <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests, hand <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> `` a major political victory'' and perhaps rekindle <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s determination to stay in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. `` We have refrained from establishing normal diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> as a demonstration of our opposition to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s illegal occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON> said. `` Were we now to agree to the establishment of interest sections in our respective capitals, this would represent a fundamental change in our policy of supporting the diplomatic isolation of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> affairs, said that establishing a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic presence in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> now `` would encourage hardliners in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> _ who do not wish to leave <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> _ by removing the pressure.'' `` We must keep the pressure on because it is working,'' he said. `` We must maintain the policy of ... no aid, no trade, no normalization.'' That policy will change eventually, but for the time being the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position must be `` Normalization _ yes _ fine _ but not now,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. As Thursday's hearing concluded, Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, the subcommittee chairman, said he agreed that the time has not come to establish diplomatic ties of any kind. `` I come away from the hearing even more convinced it would be potentially counterproductive to proceed with interest sections at this time,'' <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> said. `` I think the downside is very clear. But the time will come, and I hope it comes soon.'' <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON> said progress is being made toward ending the Vietnamese occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and that a full dialogue is under way on humanitarian issues. `` Given the current level of cooperation, we do not believe that more formal diplomatic structures are required,'' he said. But <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> opposition to setting up interest sections now `` should not be seen as a sign that the administration remains implacably hostile toward <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' `` We hold no malice toward <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> as a result of the war in <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` In fact we look forward to the time when we will be able to enter into normal diplomatic and commercial relations with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and have made it clear we are prepared to normalize'' if there is a complete Vietnamese troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.
