<HEAD>U.S. Team Heads Home After Investigating Downing of Iranian
Jetliner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The six-member team investigating the downing of <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> flight 655 left the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> on Thursday for its home base in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and was expected to complete its report on the incident next week, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. The results are not likely to be announced until mid-August at the earliest, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Rear Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fogarty </PERSON>, who heads the team, was to report to the commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>, at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Central Command headquarters in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Crist </PERSON>, in turn, will give classified and unclassified versions of the report to the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, who will pass them, with his comments, to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> for a final review. `` I understand that Adm. <PERSON> Fogarty </PERSON> is prepared to report to Gen. <PERSON> Crist </PERSON> next week,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>. `` The process involves review by Gen. <PERSON> Crist </PERSON> with his comments, then Adm. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, and the secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, and nothing ensues until that review process is completed. We do n't go public until the process is completed. In short, do n't expect anything next week,'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said. Pentagon officials have promised to release as soon as possible an unclassified report on why the USS Vicennes shot down the <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> A300 <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> with 290 aboard on July 3. At the time, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials said the officers on the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> mistook the airliner for an attacking F-14 fighter. The chief <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, told reporters Thursday that officials were trying to avoid a repetition of the delays experienced in releasing a report on the May 17, 1987, attack on the USS Stark by an Iraqi fighter. `` In the case of the Stark investigation, it was five months before the report was actually released. We'd like to do a better job of getting it to you earlier,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said it was `` unlikely'' the report would be released before <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> returns Aug. 8 from a trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. `` I do n't have a timetable for release,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fogarty </PERSON>, originally asked to complete his investigation by July 15, was granted an extension through the end of July.
