<FIRST>u w AM-Economy Bjt   07-28 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, Bjt,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spurt In Consumer Spending Fuels Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer spending increased in June at the fastest pace in 10 months, the government said Thursday, fueling concern over inflation and whether the economy will have room for production of exports. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said personal consumption spending, which includes virtually everything except interest on debt, shot up a seasonally adjusted 1.0 percent in June, the steepest climb since a 1.3 percent gain in August, two months before the October stock market crash. The report was a disappointment to many economists who are looking for growth in consumer demand to slow in order to narrow the nation's trade deficit. Excessive consumer demand implies that imports will grow and that factories will have difficulty increasing production of exports if they also have to step up manufacture of goods for domestic buyers. This strain on factory capacity could add to inflation if buyers bid up the price of scarce goods. In another economic report adding to inflation concerns, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said import prices, one of the main inflationary threats facing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy because of the weaker dollar, rose 2.7 percent in the April-June quarter, the biggest increase in more than a year. The climb followed a 1.2 percent increase in the January-March period and was the steepest since the 4.1 percent jump in the first three months of 1987, which was attributed almost entirely to rising crude oil prices. Most analysts were expecting consumer demand to slow after the October stock market crash, but that has not happened. `` There's some real danger here that we will end up with too much of a good thing,'' warned <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` This consumer spending is so strong it probably will trigger, at some point, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> actions to push interest rates higher,'' he said, adding that the move most likely will come after Aug. 16 when <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> policymakers next meet to consider monetary policy. <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, appearing before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Banking subcommittee on Thursday, repeated a warning delivered to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> two weeks ago that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> was likely to err on the side of tightening the money supply, rather than loosening. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the 4.7-percent inflation figure released Wednesday as part of the report on the second quarter gross national product was `` somewhat larger than we would have expected.'' However, he said recent economic indicators have shown no evidence that would cause the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to radically change its policy. `` There have been a lot of data ... but none has altered either my or, as far as I can judge, the board's general view as to where we are going and where we have been ... In a certain sense, it has been a period in which there have been fewer surprises than normal,'' he said. The report on consumer spending also showed that Americans' personal income jumped a healthy 0.7 percent to $ 4.04 trillion in June, the best showing in three months It followed a 0.5 percent rise in May, a modest 0.2 percent increase in April and a 1.0 percent jump in March. The gain in income in part reflected healthy increases in employment in June. The unemployment rate dropped to 5.3 percent last month, a 14-year low. With spending rising a bit faster than income, Americans' personal savings rate fell slightly to 4.3 percent, compared with 4.4 percent in May Still, the average savings rate for the first half of 1988, 4.1 percent, is up substantially from 3.2 percent in 1987. Americans' after-tax income increased a seasonally adjusted 0.8 percent in June after shooting up 2.4 percent in May. The department said tax payments declined in both May and June after higher-than-average payments in April. The department gave these details of spending: _ On durable goods, `` big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years, spending rose $ 8.6 billion in June compared with an increase of $ 2.7 billion in May _ On non-durable goods, spending rose $ 4.5 billion in June, compared with $ 4.6 billion the month before _ On services, spending rose $ 17.7 billion last month, compared with $ 11.3 billion in May <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consulting firm, said the June increase in personal spending was not as alarming as it might have been because it was likely temporarily bolstered by heavy use of electrical power to run air conditioners. `` The trend in consumer spending is about 2 percent -LRB- annual -RRB- growth. Certainly it's not driving the economy,'' she said.
