<HEAD>Polish Leader Meets Shultz, Seeks More Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polish Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON> met Thursday with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and said both sides are determined to work toward further improvements in Polish-American relations. <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON>, the first Polish foreign minister to visit <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in nine years, said he invited <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> to visit <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. The response was one of `` general approval,'' he said but no details were discussed. Polish-American relations hit bottom after <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> imposed martial law in 1981 and outlawed the independent trade union Solidarity. The reconciliation process began about two years ago, highlighted by a visit to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> last October by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the lifting by last year of the economic sanctions that had been imposed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We have normalized our relations,'' <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON> told reporters after a two-hour meeting with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and other senior officials from both sides. Although progress in bilateral relations has been made, `` we certainly hope it's not the end of the road,'' <PERSON> Olechowski </PERSON> said. He said the `` ambitions, the interests and the intentions'' of both countries are extensive and there is `` a determination on both ends to go ahead.'' There is room for increased political contacts and economic and cultural cooperation, he said. `` In all areas, there are possibilities.'' One source of friction between the two countries is <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s claim that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been providing financial support to Solidarity Polish authorities also believe that the West has been too slow in extending credits that woul