plant every single night. It was n't very good. I ca n't tell you what the food was because it was completely different.'' Miss <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said she got along well with her 13-year-old host, <PERSON> Maia </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsintsadze </PERSON>. `` It was this little girl's dream to come to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and she treated me with a lot of respect,'' she said. Miss <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said she was n't impressed with the clothing styles in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but neither was her host. `` Their clothes were kind of old fashioned,'' she said. `` Not hoop skirts, not that old. It was n't trendy like our clothes. We'd go shopping and she'd say, ` You do n't want to go to our clothes stores They're ugly. Even we do n't like them.''' <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON>, 16, said he cherished the few opportunities he had to meet people on his own. `` Although <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> is supposed to be a classless society, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> has a very strict class system and our hosts were the creme de la creme of Georgian society,'' he said. `` We did n't get to mix much with the lower classes.'' On one visit to a nearby small town, <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> said, `` people in the street starting gravitating toward us, so we started giving out our cards and some trinkets and sticks of gum.'' `` I felt great that the people from this place who were supposedly our enemies were so loving and kind to us,'' he said. `` They followed us around. The kids were shy, but they were giving me these things out of the blue because I was there and I was American.''
