<HEAD>House Approves Drought Bill After Scaling Back Dairy Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops with three grafs to update with House passage; pkup 2nd
graf pvs: ``This offers stability ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed 368-29 on Thursday a $ 5.8 billion relief package for drought-stricken farmers after scaling back a heavily debated price-support increase for the dairy industry. `` Hold on,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, declared as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved the measure. `` Help is coming in a sensible, rational, compassionate way.'' Approval came after dairy-state lawmakers responded to a drumroll of criticism by compromising on a plan to increase the price-support level for milk. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> adopted 217-181 a scaled-back version that still would leave the cost of the benefit above the $ 100 million level. `` This offers stability for our dairy farmers,'' Rep. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunderson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., declared as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved his plan to impose a 50-cent increase in the milk price-support level, but only for three months The action resolved the most heavily debated issue in the House version of the drought aid package. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> was expected to rush the measure through with equal dispatch, possibly before the night was out. Both <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> were working on highly similar versions of the bill with an eye toward putting the bill before the president at least by Aug. 11, when lawmakers are set to flee <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s summer heat `` This bill is the most generous disaster relief package ever considered by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., said as debate began in that chamber At the core of both bills is a provision that would pay drought-stricken farmers 65 percent of lost earnings from crop damage in excess of 35 percent of the harvest expected before blazing sun and a shortage of rainfall hammered the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Key provisions also would streamline and expand government programs to aid livestock and dairy producers forced to pay escalating feed costs because the drought has burned away a substantial quantity of hay and feedgrains. <PERSON> Gunderson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Penny </PERSON> offered their plan to scale back the dairy provision after the original version came under criticism from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as excessively costly. Sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, R-Vt., the original version would have imposed an increase in the dairy price support level of 50 cents on Oct. 1 to $ 11.10 for each 100 pounds of milk That would cost consumers, at most, a few cents per gallon in increased milk prices. Dairy-state lawmakers said the cost to the government would be $ 145 million, while <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, on Wednesday night that the actual cost would be $ 300 million. Lawmakers said that the <LOCATION> Gunderson-Penny </LOCATION> plan, limiting the increase to a three-month period from April through June next year, would reduce costs by perhaps $ 30 million. Dairy-state lawmakers have been saying that the increase is warranted to avert a milk shortage looming over the country next spring and because milk producers have faced greater feed costs while not receiving the disaster payments that the bill allocates for crop producers. But the increase has come under fire not only from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration but from an array of business groups and even farm organizations that most often ally themselves with dairymen in matters involving farm-subsidy legislation. `` This is a most dangerous and wrongheaded precedent,'' Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Kan </LOCATION>., told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in urging it to slash any price-support increase from the legislation `` Should those in the cattle business, in the sheep and the poultry business, be asked to pay the same high feed costs without some similar subsidy _ that's not fair. Before taking up the dairy issue, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved an amendment sponsored by de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> that would bring the estimate cost to $ 5.8 billion. When the measure came to the floor, the price tag was placed at $ 6.9 billion by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> staff. The reason was because of a provision that would have required the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to pay half of the cost of reseeding and other seeding of drought-burned pastures in 20 states. The measure sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, D-Ala., was harnessed to the bill when the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was racing to wrap up work and later estimated to have a $ 1.2 billion cost <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>'s amendment reduced the overall cost of the bill by shrinking the seeding provision. Even then, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, acknowledged Thursday morning that there was no way to be perfectly sure of exactly how much the drought bill would cost. Farm lawmakers have been saying that fiscal watchdogs worried about the spending level have nothing to complain about because it would be less than federal savings realized because of the drought. But <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said there was no certainty. `` The art of economics is not a precise one,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said.
