<HEAD>Officials To Discuss Prospects for Angola Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top Soviet and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials will meet in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> starting Sunday to exchange views on the prospects for a negotiated withdrawal of all foreign forces from southwestern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Assistant Secretary of State for African Affairs <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> will lead the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation and Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamyshin </PERSON> will head the Soviet side. The two days of talks will take place on the eve of a new round of negotiations aimed at achieving the withdrawal of foreign forces from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and Namibian independence from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The negotiations, also set for <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, involve <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> playing a mediating role. The talks will be held from Aug. 2-4 with <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> representing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He has spent seven years attempting to arrange a settlement but, with five armies involved in the conflict and the negotiations plagued by mutual distrust among the participants, the task has not been easy. During the last round of talks, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> reached agreement on a statement of principles governing future negotiations. The next round is expected to include discussions on a timetable for the withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban forces from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> also has several thousand troop