<HEAD>Biography Details Fortas' Resignation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> was tricked into taking a seat on the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and later was bluffed into becoming the first justice ever to resign in disgrace, the author of a new book said Thursday. Using records President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> once ordered destroyed, author <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> also details <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON>' extensive role as an adviser in the president's inner circle, unprecedented for a sitting justice. `` The book is like a murder mystery: Who killed <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON>' career? said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, whose research took him to libraries in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. His book, `` Fortas: The Rise and Ruin of a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>,'' will be released Friday <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> repeatedly asked <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> to accept the nomination for a seat on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, but the prominent <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney each time turned down the offer. <ORGANIZATION> LBJ </ORGANIZATION> got <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> to accept the job in 1965 by saying the president needed his friend's help drafting a statement to the press on a troop increase in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. While they rode the White House elevator to the East Room to meet the press, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> told <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> that in a few minutes he would be announced as the nominee to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Four years after he joined the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> resigned for accepting a $ 20,000-a-year salary to work for a foundation set up by millionaire industrialist <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> while he was a member of the court. <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justices made $ 39,500 at the time. Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> bluffed <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> into leaving the court by intimating it had more damaging evidence than the money from <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON>, which had been returned, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> discovered photocopies of <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> documents in the papers of the late Chief Justice <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON>, who died in 1982, `` represents the turning point in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> history in the 20th century,'' said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. Without <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON>, liberal <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> would have remained on the bench and might have succeeded <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> as chief justice during the <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> administration, said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, 36, a professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Instead, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> persuaded <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> to leave the court to become ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to make room for <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejected <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON>' nomination as chief justice and his 1969 resignation allowed <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> to appoint two members of the court and making the court more conservative, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> ordered all his files on <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> destroyed during the tough <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation hearings for <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> as chief justice, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. Aides disobeyed the order and sent the papers, locked in a safe, to the <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> Library </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who spent six years researching his book, found them. <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> destroyed all his own personal and professional records, even typed copies of speeched he delivered. In the file at the <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> found records of White House meetings <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> attended on proposed legislation, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s speeches and the Vietnam War. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who had only one interview with <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON> before he died, said <PERSON> Fortas </PERSON>' soft, melodious voice, sharp analytical mind and ability to convert complex legal issues into understandable terms caused his rise from poverty in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s inner circles <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> also explored extra-judicial activities in `` The Brandeis-Frankfurter Connection: The Secret Political Activities of <ORGANIZATION> Two </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justices,'' which was published in 1982.
