<FIRST>u w AM-BankDeregulation-Glance     07-28 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Deregulation-Glance,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bank Deregulation Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the key provisions of far-reaching bank deregulation legislation approved, 30-20, Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Banking Committee:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SECURITIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The bill grants bank holding companies the power, through separately capitalized subsidiaries, to underwrite corporate bonds, mutual funds, commerical paper, corporate debt convertible to stock and securities backed by mortgages and other consumer loans. A bank would not have to form a holding company to underwrite municipal bonds or to sell shares in a mutual fund underwritten by another company. Securities firms retain exclusive rights to the biggest area of securities underwriting: corporate stock.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SAFEGUARDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Affiliated banks and securities firms are barred from sharing the same name, logo, advertising or premises. The securities subsidiary will be required to inform customers they are not dealing with a federally insured bank.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INSURANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The legislation limits banks' ability to expand into insurance. National banks and state-chartered banks owned by holding companies, which are regulated on the federal level, will not be allowed to underwrite insurance, unless they already do so. Free-standing state banks remain governed by state laws. If state law permits, state banks will be allowed to sell insurance, unless they are owned by an out-of-state holding company. There is an exemption for national banks serving communities of 5,000 population and less.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REAL ESTATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 National banks and state banks owned by a holding company will be banned for two years from entering the real estate business. Banks currently engaged in real estate activies may continue.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONSUMERS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Banks will be required to demonstrate a good record of lending to poor neighborhoods before receiving <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> permission to engage in new powers. Agricultural banks with assets of less than $ 50 million and all commercial banks with assets less than $ 25 million are exempted Banks will also be required to offer low-fee, low-service `` lifeline'' checking accounts to poor customers. They can be opened for as little as $ 25 and can have a balance as high as $ 1,000. However, customers will have to pay extra to write more than 10 checks per month. Special checking accounts must be offered to poor people who only want to cash government checks up to $ 1,500 such as Social Security and welfare payments. No more than $ 2 may be charged per check for the cashing service.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880728-0165 </DOCNO>
