<FIRST>u i AM-ChemicalWeapons 1stLd-Writethru a0652 07-28 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Weapons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Discloses Production Sites of Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Pentagon comment, LEADS with 3 grafs, picking
up 3rd pvs `The United States' and INSERTS 7 grafs after 11th pvs
`The production', PICKING up 13th `Delegates have.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official made the first disclosure of the location of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> production facilities for chemical weapons in an attempt Thursday to speed talks aimed at banning the manufacture and use of such weapons. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said chemical weapons were being produced or stored at only two of the five sites named by <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate to the 40-nation Conference on Disarmament. <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> told the conference his announcement was an unprecedented step toward greater openness. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> previously declared the location of its stockpiles and the types of chemicals contained in them, but not the amount or the location of the production facilities. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has declared the amount of its stockpiles, but not their location, nor the location of production sites. <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> said his delegation hoped the declaration would `` contribute both to greater confidence and to the negotiation of related provisions'' of a convention banning the production, stockpiling and use of chemical weapons. The <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> conference has been negotiating such a convention for 20 years. This year's summer session began July 7. `` The declaration we are making today is unprecedented,'' <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> said, adding that no other conference member had provided information on chemical weapons production facilities. `` We urge other countries that possess chemical weapons production facilities to declare the locations of their facilities and to outline how the facilities would be destroyed,'' he said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are the only two members of the conference who have acknowledged possessing chemical weapons. Many conference members have declared that they do not possess chemical weapons, but <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> indicated in his speech that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not believe some of them. He declined to say which countries. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has said previously it believes about 15 nations possess such weapons, but it consistently declines to identify them. In December, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> said its chemical weapon stocks total 50,000 tons, but Western experts have estimated the total is much higher. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> also said it had no stocks outside its borders, a contention that also has been challenged by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The production facilities declared by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Pine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bluff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, which produces the new binary chemical weapons; <ORGANIZATION> Muscle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shoals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ammunition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Depot </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> Proving Ground in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. At the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, Lt. Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapla </PERSON> said chemical weapons currently are produced or stored only at Pine Bluff and Muscle Shoals. `` These are locations which are at present or were at one time involved in the production of chemical weapons,'' <PERSON> Chapla </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON>'s list. `` At <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, there is no chemical weapon production, testing or storage going on.'' <PERSON> Chapla </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Aberdeen </ORGANIZATION> is used to test some components of the current generation of chemical weapons but is not used to produce, store or test the binary, or dual chemical, weapons the military now uses. `` Our focus now is the production of binary chemical, principally at Pine Bluff,'' he said. Some work is also done at Muscle Shoals on one of the chemicals used in binary weapons but the weapon is not deadly until the two chemicals are combined, <PERSON> Chapla </PERSON> said. `` The binary program is such that you never have a complete weapon stored in any one place,'' he said. `` The two chemicals are never kept together and they will not be mated until just before firing.'' At the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> conference, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also submitted to the conference ideas for methods to destroy chemical weapons under an eventual ban. Delegates have drafted many parts of a chemical weapons ban. The main unresolved issue is how to guard against cheating. Other problems include ensuring that the maximum number of countries joins the ban, maintaining a military balance while stocks are gradually destroyed, and precisely defining chemical weapons. <PERSON> Friedersdorf </PERSON> said in his speech that `` an agreed definition -LRB- of chemical weapons -RRB- is within reach'' and the conference has made `` significant progress'' toward resolving some issues in the past months. He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
