<HEAD>With AM-Mandela-Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fire that destroyed her home Thursday was one of many hardships that have beset <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> since her husband <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader, was sent to prison 26 years ago. She has spent 17 months in solitary confinement, lived in isolation, been arrested several times and passed virtually her entire adult life under stringent police restrictions and public scrutiny. Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> is 54 and was trained as a social worker. She has become a leading campaigner against apartheid and black activists often call her `` Mother of the Nation.'' Her commanding presence, controversial statements and willingness to confront authorities has made her one of the most visible symbols of opposition to white domination in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Another result of her prominence is that some of her personal hardships become public events. When she visits her husband at <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, journalists are there. By the time she reached her burned-out home Thursday it was surrounded by firefighters, police and journalists who already had wandered through the smoldering remains. Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> saw the crowd, stayed in her car and went directly to an office she maintains nearby. Friends said the house held all her belongings, including wedding photographs, family documents and the piano her husband used to play. Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> moved into the modest four-room bungalow in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s huge black township, after she married <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> in 1958. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> had owned the house and lived in it since the 1940s. It has been shot at and stoned by attackers who have not been identified. Police visit it regularly. After <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s arrest in 1962, Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> began receiving banning orders that prohibited her from addressing public gatherings, meeting with more than one person and entering places ranging from schools to printing houses. They applied from 1963 to 1986 except for one 18-month period. From May 1969 to September 1970 she was held in solitary confinement, tried twice under the Terrorism Act and acquitted both times. Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> was imprisoned for six months in 1974 for violating the banning order and detained for four months in 1976 after riots in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. A banning order issued in 1977 forced her to leave the <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> house and move to <LOCATION> Brandfort </LOCATION> in the rural <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>. Her home and office there were burned down in 1985 and she was allowed to return to the home in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> a year later. Her defiance undimmed, Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> declared on her return: `` I should never have been away from home in the first place. I am grateful to no one. It was my right to be at home.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Mandelas </ORGANIZATION> have two daughters. <PERSON> Zindzi </PERSON>, 27, lives with her mother, and <PERSON> Zenani </PERSON>, 29, is studying at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with her husband, a member of <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>'s royal family.
