<HEAD>Mandela Home Burned by Teen-Agers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th `State of emergency' to include
Chikane comment; picks up 8th `Mrs. Mandela'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos JOH1,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The home that has belonged to <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and his family since the 1940s was gutted in an arson attack Thursday that apparently involved a teen-gang dispute and was not aimed at Mandela himself. Police said no one was hurt and no arrests were made. Capt. <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloomberg </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> that 30 to 50 black high school students stoned the home of the imprisoned leader of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, doused it with gasoline and set it afire. Neighbors and black journalists said some attackers wore jackets of <PERSON> Daliwonga </PERSON> high school in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, and were involved in a dispute Wednesday with the young <PERSON> black </PERSON> `` comrades'' who guard the home. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON>, a prominent anti-apartheid activist, was bound for a news conference concerning detainees when she learned of the fire, which broke out about noon -LRB- 6 a.m. EDT -RRB-. Her daughter, <PERSON> Zindzi </PERSON>, 27, and her two grandchildren, who also live at the four-room home, were away at the time. But neighbors and journalists said some of the `` comrades'' who often travel with Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and guard her home were at the house when the fire began. State of emergency regulations restrict reporting about unrest, security force action, treatment of detainees, some forms of protest and a range of statements classified as subversive. The Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, said leaders in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> and other black townships had been asked `` to call upon the community not to act emotionally so they do not create a situation where there is a spiral of violence.'' He said an attempt would be made to talk to the principal and the students of the school involved to ease the situation. He said young men who congregate around the Mandela home were told `` not to act without thinking or with revenge.'' Although the dispute is local, he said, `` when it is <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s house that is attacked, that makes it a national issue Anybody who attacks a well-known leader's house like that one would know they would anger the people in the community and cause them to take action.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> arrived by car about an hour later and viewed the blackened windows and burned furniture in the yard from inside the car. She then was driven to her nearby offices where she conducts social welfare projects. The `` comrades,'' some wearing jackets of the <ORGANIZATION> Mandela </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> soccer club, sponsored by the family, pushed journalists away from the office. One threatened to burn a photographer's car. Later, attorney <PERSON> Amrichand </PERSON> <PERSON> Soma </PERSON> told reporters <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> was reached at <LOCATION> Pollsmoor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, where he is serving a life term for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-dominated government, and said no statement should be made. However, <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mokoena </PERSON>, a family friend and head of the <ORGANIZATION> Release </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mandela </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` The community must ... put an end to this. Anyone who would think of attacking <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s house represents the forces of darkness.'' Journalists were allowed to enter the still-smoking home in the <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, while black police with shotguns kept a crowd of 300 neighbors away. A sodden carpet of hot, black ash covered everything. Flames flickered in a side room. The house was filled with steam from the heat and the water. Firemen pushed clothes out a bedroom window, pulled a smoldering mattress outside, shoved smoking cabinets and chairs onto the lawn. All the contents, including framed wedding pictures and the family piano, were destroyed. Mrs. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> has lived in the house periodically since she married <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> in 1958. Last year she built a mansion on a hill overlooking this huge black township outside of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, a few blocks from the burned home. But <PERSON> Mokoena </PERSON> said the new house is not habitable and she would spend the night with friends. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> moved into the house with his first wife, <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON>, in the 1940s and raised his two sons and his oldest daughter there. <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> lives in the Xhosa tribal homeland of <LOCATION> Transkei </LOCATION>.
