<HEAD>Government Suspends Journalist Registration Plan Temporarily</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government ordered a temporary suspension Thursday of rules that would require some journalists to register or face penalties, including jail. The regulations were to take effect Sunday. Media groups in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and abroad accused the South African government of attempting to make further inroads on press freedom. <PERSON> Stoffel </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, home affairs minister, said registration of journalists `` remains a matter of grave concern for the government,'' but the regulations were suspended temporarily because of `` practical considerations.'' He said they would be reviewed, but did not indicate when a decision would be made. The broadly worded rules now say anyone carrying out `` news-agency'' business must register or face a 10-year prison term or a $ 8,500 fine. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest news agency, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, and such major international agencies as The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> are exempt. Local journalists who work part-time for some of the world's large news organizations would be required to register if, as many do, they had more than one employer Lawyers say the definition of a `` news agency'' is so broad that major newspapers that exchange stories, church and political groups that publish newsletters, and businesses that issue regular press statements on their operations could be included if the government wished. Under the regulations, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> could remove journalists from the registration list and prevent them from working if he objected to their reporting. He already has broad censorship powers that allow him to close publications and expel foreign journalists. The latest regulations appear aimed at small, local news agencies but most news organizations operating in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would be affected because they get reports from those agencies. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has said local agencies endanger public safety by reporting unfavorably on police activities, forced removals of poor blacks and labor disputes in rural areas that other news organizations do not cover regularly. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correspondents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has said even journalists not required to register would be compromised because they would be seen as having favored status with the government. State-of-emergency regulations already in force restrict reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of detainees, some forms of protest and a broad range of statement the government considers subversive. Under the official apartheid policy, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no voice in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate residential districts, schools and health services.
