<HEAD>Law Center To Build Memorial In Birthplace Of The Civil Rights
Movement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The designer of the Vietnam War Memorial said Thursday she hopes her latest work, a somber monument to the civil rights movement, will make people remember the bloody struggle for racial equality. `` The Vietnam Memorial has an impact on the immediate family. This is about the importance of not forgetting the civil rights movement,'' said <PERSON> Maya </PERSON> <PERSON> Lin </PERSON>, whose black wall in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> bearing the names of dead American soldiers has prompted emotional outpourings. Ms. <PERSON> Lin </PERSON> said the planned civil rights monument will bear the names of about 30 people killed during the civil rights era of the 1950s and'60s. `` The name is one of the most magical ways to bring back a person,'' she said. `` It's more real than any one image can be.'' The $ 350,000 memorial will be located on a slope in front of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poverty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a Montgomery-based, public-interest law firm specializing in civil rights issues. The memorial will be a short walk from the church where a young Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> gained prominence by leading the <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> bus boycott, often cited as the start of the contemporary American civil rights movement. Ms. <PERSON> Lin </PERSON>'s design calls for an upper plaza with a quiet pool and water that cascades down the face of a curved, black wall 40 feet long. Inscribed in gold leaf on the wall will be a section of King's `` I Have a Dream Speech,'' saying: `` We will not be satisfied until justice rolls down like water and righteousness like a mighty stream.'' In the lower plaza, a circular stone table 12 feet in diameter will be inscribed with time lines and the names of people killed during the civil rights movement from 1955 to 1968. Water emerging from the center of the table will flow evenly across its surface. The time lines will begin with the Aug. 28, 1955, murder of <PERSON> Emmett </PERSON> <PERSON> Till </PERSON> in Money, Miss. Till, a black man, was lynched after saying `` Bye, baby,'' to a white woman. The historical review will end April 4, 1968: the day King was assassinated in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn </LOCATION>. In addition to Till and King, among those listed will be <PERSON> Medgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> official gunned down in front of his home in 1963; four children killed in 1963 when a bomb exploded at the 16th Street Baptist Church in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>; and three men shot to death in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, during the `` Freedom Summer'' of 1964. Construction of the memorial will begin later this year, with completion scheduled for May 1989. The project will be funded by proceeds from the recent sale of property adjacent to law center.
