<TEXT>
 `` Road,'' a gritty, grimy and thoroughly fascinating journey through industrial <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, puts most of the audience where the action is _ right in the middle of an unnamed <ORGANIZATION> Lancashire </ORGANIZATION> town dying during <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s boom times. This provocative play, which opened Thursday at off-Broadway's La Mama Annex, lets theatergoers wander a dismal thoroughfare and mingle with the town's citizens The less adventurous can perch along a three-sided balcony and observe the action, but the distance would seem to dilute the drama. To get the full effect of <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON>' masterful direction, it's better to be right down on the road, a depressingly realistic environment designed by <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> does a remarkable job, not only with the actors but with the audience which follows the flow of the play across the playing area with minimal instruction from the performers. The setting reflects the dead-end dreams of its inhabitants. The hulk of an abandoned car sits on one corner of the playing area. Squat, dilapidated homes line one side of the street. Other open spaces become the oppressive parlors and bedrooms of these people who have lost all hope. Playwright <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cartwright </PERSON> has written some bitter yet often very funny vignettes about their threadbare existence and stitched them together by creating a scruffy master of ceremonies named Scullery. The character is played with a roguish charm by <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>. Scullery introduces the residents of the road, all of them in the process of going out for the evening. `` Going out'' for most of them means getting drunk. Several of the scenes are etched in despair. Audiences meet the middle-aged <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> who, in a poignant soliloquy, laments the days long ago when people had jobs, good times and felt `` safe.'' `` I ca n't get away from the past,'' he says. `` But no matter what they say, I ca n't see how that time could turn into this time.'' The hopelessness of today is reiterated throughout the play and <PERSON> Cartwright </PERSON> offers several variations on that desolation. In another sketch, a young man named <PERSON> Joey </PERSON> is on a hunger strike. `` They rush you from the cradle to the grave. But now we've come to a standstill, no job, no hope,'' he murmurs to his good-natured girlfriend who joins him in the starvation pact. There's also a defiance in the desperation, particularly in the play's powerful last scene when two young men pick up two girls and bring them home for booze and sex. The quartet is moved by <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> Redding </PERSON>'s recording of `` Try a Little Tenderness,'' and as they become progressively drunker, they chant fiercely, `` Somehow _ might escape.'' You get the impression that if they do n't, something terrible is going to happen. <PERSON> Cartwright </PERSON>'s play is overtly political and his message occasionally becomes heavy-handed. There are references to <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and what kind of country <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> has become under <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> rule. But his characters are immensely human _ often humorous, often repugnant and completely believable. The play's seven actors portray a variety of characters and their versatility is a marvel. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacon </PERSON> gets the most difficult workout. He must switch from the impassioned hunger striker to a drunkenly catatonic soldier. As the striker's simple-minded girlfriend, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cusack </PERSON> projects a delicacy that shines through all the despair. She radiates a sweetness that is captivating. Equally fine work comes from <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bamman </PERSON> as the nostaglic <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON>; <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Aidem </PERSON> as an old hag trying to get dressed to go out for an evening of fun; <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Wincott </PERSON>, an unnerving and menacing Skinhead, and <PERSON> Jayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> as a sassy tart. `` Road'' is a joint production of <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> and La Mama. For <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, it is another feather in an already crowded cap of shows that includes `` Anything Goes,'' `` Sarafina!'' and `` Speed-the-Plow.''
