<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The administration on Thursday projected the federal deficit for the upcoming budget year at $ 140.1 billion _ short of the trigger for across-the-board spending cuts _ but warned that a hefty drought-relief bill could cause the automatic reductions to kick in. The new deficit estimate, covering the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, is $ 5.9 billion below the $ 146 billion level that would force politically painful cuts under the Gramm-Rudman budget law. However, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, said that the drought relief bill and several other spending proposals could quickly wipe out the cushion and trigger the spending cuts, which would take effect right before the November elections. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> supports drought relief, a popular initiative in an election year, but he said the president does n't want to `` use the plight of the farmers as an opportunity to make a Christmas tree out of that bill'' by loading it up with provisions that have little to do with drought relief. Later Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved a drought bill providing up to $ 5.8 billion in assistance for farmers, while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a drought relief measure estimated to cost between $ 5.85 billion and $ 6.55 billion. The administration is also fighting to hold down spending on other measures pending before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, including anti-drug legislation, trade legislation and aid for the hungry and homeless. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said if all of those measures were adopted, the 1989 deficit would increase by between $ 6.4 billion and $ 8.7 billion, enough even at the low end of the estimate to trigger the spending cuts. `` We ca n't do all the things that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has on its list right now,'' he told reporters during a White House briefing. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has got to pare down and make sure it does n't go over these limits.'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, D-Pa., agreed that the administration's mid-session budget review showed `` we may be moving uncomfortably close'' to automatic spending cuts `` It is clear from this report that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration will have to make difficult choices in the months ahead. All of the urgent needs of the nation can not be funded at the levels most of us would support in less difficult times,'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. Under the Gramm-Rudman act, the administration is required to estimate the coming year's fiscal budget deficit by mid-August. The White House budget office must then adjust that estimate in October to take into account any new legislation. If such legislation pushes the deficit past the trigger amount of $ 146 billion, automatic spending cuts of more than $ 10 billion automatically take effect in October, right before the fall elections, with half of the cuts taken out of domestic spending and half out of military spending. The administration's new budget estimates, which are based on updated economic and spending projections, predicted that the deficit in the current fiscal year would be $ 152.3 billion. This is slightly higher than the $ 146.7 billion deficit estimate the administration made in February, but it is still well below the deficit estimates of $ 160 billion or more that were being made by many private economists at the time. Better-than-expected economic growth, which has pushed the unemployment rate down to a 14-year-low and boosted government tax revenues, was credited for lowering the shortfall. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a private consulting firm, said his current estimates were close to the administration's forecasts for this year and next year. The 1987 budget deficit was $ 150.4 billion as a one-time windfall from tax overhaul resulted in a big improvement from the $ 221.1 billion record deficit suffered in 1986. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, noting that the administration's original forecast was scorned as a `` rosy scenario,'' blamed higher spending in such areas as deposit insurance for missing the administration's February target The budget review said that the bank and savings and loan insurance funds would pay out $ 4.6 billion more this year than had been originally budgeted because of high failure rates at financial institutions in the depressed <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>. The deficit target under the Gramm-Rudman legislation for the upcoming fiscal year is $ 136 billion, but the legislation says automatic spending cuts can be avoided if the government's deficit projection is within $ 10 billion of that figure. Thus, for 1989, any estimate below $ 146 billion would avoid the need for spending cuts.
</TEXT>
