fire acreage to 2,800 and increase damage to homes, etc. Picks up
17th graf pvs, `Although cooler...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos RAP2, YNP3, LaserColor YNP5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An arson forest fire that has burned into the western edges of this city expanded and switched direction Thursday and more subdivisions were ordered evacuated, officials said. `` It's out of control. It has expanded drastically since I was there last evening,'' Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, efforts to block a fire burning toward Old Faithful geyser in Yellowstone National Park were hampered by what normally would be good firefighting weather _ cool, damp conditions slowed a backfire intended to head off one of seven major fires. Fires also burned in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. Three subdivisions in western <LOCATION> Rapid </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> were ordered evacuated Thursday as a precaution as wind whipped a fire in the heavily forested <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. Later Thursday, officials suggested that residents leave another rural housing area. Reports that the fire was arson brought strong reaction from residents. `` I ca n't believe there's people that sick,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON>, who could n't return home after a dental appointment because of the evacuation order. `` It floors me to think that someone could cause that much destruction and devastaton to so many people. Fire officials did not know how many homes were involved but said the number was in the hundreds. `` It's almost being defended totally by air at the present time because it is in those canyons and the ground crews simply can not fight the fire,'' <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> said in an interview from his office in <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON>. The wind switched from the southeast to the north during the morning and gained speed, he said. That combined with a forecast high of 100 degrees `` does not bode well for fighting the fire,'' the governor said. The fire had been declared 70 percent contained by late Thursday after burning an estimated 2,800 acres. Fifteen homes, 32 outbuildings, 14 vehicles and a bridge had been destroyed. Earlier Thursday, about half of the 1,000 people who were told to leave their homes Wednesday were allowed to return. <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> was at the scene Wednesday and saw a barn and a house catch fire no more than 200 yards away. The buildings were engulfed in seconds. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopp </PERSON>, the fire incident commander, said Wednesday that the fire was the work of an arsonist. And he said authorities have been investigating a series of about 50 fires dating back to May that are believed to have been started by the same person. A 14-year-old boy was arrested in <LOCATION> Rapid </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after a small fire was reported on a ridge overlooking the town. But police said they did not think he was responsible for setting the main fire on Tuesday. Fires inside <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> had charred 95,135 acres by Thursday evening, about 4 percent of the park's 2.2 million acres. Although cooler temperatures, higher humidity and scattered showers aided fire control efforts, the conditions created problems for firefighters attempting to start a 6-mile backfire along the eastern edge of the 8,500-acre North Fork fire that was within six miles of Old Faithful. But the same conditions helped firefighters outside the park and officials in the <LOCATION> Bridger-Teton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> prepared to release some of the 690 firefighters battling the 24,400-acre Mink Creek fire in the forest's <LOCATION> Teton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wilderness </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldapfel </PERSON>, fire information officer. The seven major fires in the p