ON> about 35 miles west of <LOCATION> Missoula </LOCATION>. There were 51 wind-whipped fires burning across <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>; firefighters were battling only 16 of them. <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON> said fires this summer have blackened 1.4 million acres in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. Ten families remained out of their homes in the area of the 3,000-acre <LOCATION> Willis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulch </LOCATION> fire northeast of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, and the state imposed strict fire restrictions, due to go into effect at midnight, on government land throughout the dry southern part of the state. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, firefighters were working on scores of small fires throughout the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, most of them caused by lightning. But a fire that burned about 30 acres Wednesday near <LOCATION> Coulterville </LOCATION>, destroying four structures and forcing the evacuation of up to 70 homes, was blamed on a careless 13-year-old smoker.
