<HEAD>Wedtech Prosecutor: Defense Attacks on Meese are a Smokescreen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal prosecutor ridiculed defense tactics at the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> corruption trial Thursday, saying they were a bid to cloud the case with allegations against Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and six others on trial since mid-March are charged with a racketeering conspiracy that allegedly turned <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> into a vehicle for bribery and kickbacks. Prosecutors claim <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>, a now-defunct military contractor, grew into a multimillion-dollar concern by committing fraud against a government program that set aside contracts for minority-owned businesses. A key element of the defense case, however, was the claim that corrupt <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> executives had connections to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> White House insiders like <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and did not need to buy <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s influence to obtain the no-bid defense contracts. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, in a day-long rebuttal of the defense's closing arguments, compared the so-called `` Meese defense'' to a squid that `` squirts black ink into the sea, eveything gets cloudy, everything gets muddy. `` It's impossible to see the creature and he escapes,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, adding that his admittedly `` silly parable'' showed `` what so much of the defense in this case has been.'' He compared it to `` a squid under attack. Talk about something else. Do n't talk about the facts. Create a diversion and a smokescreen so there's a lot of ink and muddy waters.'' In his closing argument Thursday, <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRossa </PERSON> said <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was `` at the core of the conspiracy'' and accused the attorney general of orchestrating corruption by investigating <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>'s competitors while allowing the company to pay his legal fees during his confirmation hearings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Another prosecutor, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Little, shocked the courtroom last week when he conceded in his summation that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> `` was a sleaze'' but said his activities had no bearing on the guilt or innocence of <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> and his co-defendants. In his rebuttal argument, <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> hammered at that point. `` The biggest smokescreen or diversion in this case _ to protect them -LRB- the defendants -RRB- from the truth _ is <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was under scrutiny for some time because of his <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> connections, but a special prosecutor in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, determined there was insufficient evidence to charge <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> with wrongdoing. However, <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> questioned the attorney general's ethics on several issues <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has said he will leave office later this summer. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> was to instruct the jury on the law governing its deliberations Friday, before it began weighing evidence in the four-month-old trial. <PERSON> Motley </PERSON>'s charge to the jury was expected to last all day.
