<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> appealed to <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> on Thursday to investigate reported massacres of hundreds of civilians by government forces fighting rebels. The London-based human rights group also called on Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON>'s government to repeal amputation and flogging as legal penalties. In a 10-page report, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> urged <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> to `` take firm measures to assert the rule of law'' and establish independent inquries into reported massacres in the southern part of the East African nation. The report followed a letter the group sent to <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> in May outlining its concerns over reported human rights abuses. Amnesty said it received no reply. The Sudanese People's <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, based in the Christian and animist south, has waged a guerrilla war against Moslem-dominated governments in the northern capital of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> since 1983. The rebels oppose Islamic law, introduced by ousted President <PERSON> Gafaar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON>, which imposes amputation and flogging for certain offenses, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said. No amputations have been carried out since the military toppled <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON> while he was visiting <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1985, but floggings continue and courts still pass amputation sentences, the report said. Massacres of unarmed civilians have taken place `` apparently because they belonged to an ethnic group regarded as sympathetic to or supportive of the -LRB- rebels -RRB-,'' it said. Soldiers and militiamen reportedly massacred 1,000 to 2,000 <ORGANIZATION> Dinka </ORGANIZATION> tribesmen in the town of <LOCATION> Wau </LOCATION> in August and September 1987, it said. Hundreds of other <LOCATION> Dinka </LOCATION> civilians were burned to death by mobs in the town of Ad-Daien when police failed to intervene, the report said. Relief agencies have estimated that fighting has displaced up to half the 6 million residents of the south, the report said. Hundreds of thousands of them fled to neighboring <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, where the government is fighting its own civil war against rebels in the north.
