<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` L.A. Law,'' the gripping show whose behind-the-scenes power struggles were as intriguing as its onscreen courtroom dramas, swept the nominations Thursday for the 40th annual Emmy Awards. Cable programs, eligible for Emmy competition for the first time, drew 15 nominations, accounting for less than 5 percent of the available categories. The nominations were noteworthy, too, for who was overlooked.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Service began a 16-month, $ 700,000 quest Thursday to lick the problem of stamps that do n't stay stuck, urging industry to produce an adhesive to serve as a `` seat belt for a stamp. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morison </PERSON>, a senior assistant postmaster general, made it clear during a daylong conference at <ORGANIZATION> Battelle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> that the post office was serious about development of a superior, water-activated adhesive. `` Unfortunately, the news that we have made in the last few days is that we're spending a lot of money on something the press perceives as insignificant,'' <PERSON> Morison </PERSON> told about 100 adhesive industry executives and technical experts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A news leak on a covert plan to undermine Panamanian military ruler <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> came from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and was a `` set-up deal'' to make it look like the disclosure came from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., chairman of the panel, and the committee's ranking Republican, Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, said they believed the leak was a `` heavy-handed'' attempt to derail a bill that would tighten congressional oversight of covert operations, and also to enhance Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s political `` I think the matter was handled in such a way as to set up members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to make them appear the source of the leak,'' said <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>. `` I am offended by it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is pressing the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for maps showing the locations of millions of mines scattered in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> during the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s eight-year occupation so that millions of Afghan refugees can go home, a top <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official says. At the same time, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, in a meeting Thursday with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, allayed concerns that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was reneging on its timetable for withdrawing troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` This impression has just been dispelled,'' <PERSON> Sahabzada </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> are comparing notes on how to monitor the Soviet withdrawal _ and on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s future after the troops are gone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The home that has belonged to <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and his family since the 1940s was gutted in an arson attack Thursday that apparently involved a teen-gang dispute and was not aimed at Mandela himself. Police said no one was hurt and no arrests were made. Police Capt. <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloomberg </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> that 30 to 50 black high school students stoned the home of the imprisoned leader of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, doused it with gasoline and set it afire.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Armed supporters of American-born Rabbi <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahane </PERSON> are patrolling Arab sectors of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> in vans and on foot in defiance of police, who have arrested 20 of the vigilantes in six days. On one patrol Thursday, four men whose ages ranged from 16 to 24 drove through <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> east </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> to the Jewish community of <PERSON> Neve </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaacov </PERSON> and escorted bus No. 25, often a target of Arab stoning attacks, to the center of the city. Officials fear such patrols by members of <PERSON> Kahane </PERSON>'s Kach movement, which advocates expelling all Arabs from Israeli-controlled territory, will provoke violence between the <LOCATION> Holy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s 135,000 Palestinians and 340,000 Jews.
