<FIRST>a a PM-TerrifiedTown Adv03   07-28 1043</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Terrified Town, Adv 03,1081</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday PMs, Aug. 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Series Of Arsons Has Remote Town On Edge</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The morning after someone burned down <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartford </PERSON>'s home, friends and neighbors came by to offer help and sympathy. Standing in the ashes of all he'd lost, he found himself wondering if any of them had lit the match. `` People are coming by and you think, ` I wonder if it's Jim or <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> or <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>,' `` <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> said. Fifteen unsolved arsons since May 5 have reduced the town of 850 to waves of rumor and fearful speculation about everyone. Knowing that most of the fires have been set around midnight or 1 a.m., many residents do n't leave their houses after dark. In most homes, someone keeps watch through the night. In many, there's a gun near the door. Morning talk in the Old Corner Store drifts to how many days have passed since the last fire. `` People in town have changed,'' said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON>, whose family escaped its burning house when her husband heard something in the yard and smelled smoke. `` Everybody used to be very happy and smiling, laughing, talking. Now it's long faces, tired, nervous.'' The town, 125 miles north of <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, is `` on the defensive now,'' <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> said. `` People are staying pretty much to themselves because no one knows who it is.'' `` It could be one of your best friends, someone you've known for years and never suspected,'' <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> agreed. By daylight, <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>'s 100 square miles of fields, forests and back roads nestle in the shadow of the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>' Presidential Range Tourists on their way from <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> pass through the village's three blocks, where they find the Old Corner Store, three gas stations, a post office and public library and little more. With no local industry, most residents commute to nearby towns for work. About 30 volunteers make up the fire department. <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> has no police force. The town depends on state police in <LOCATION> Twin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION>, about 12 miles away. `` You see someone who looks haggard and drawn in the corner store on Sunday morning and you know it's because they were up all night,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>, a state senator. `` We're not unlike the hostages in a hijacking. It's a feeling of helplessness.'' The fires that began in fields and brush escalated to barns, unoccupied houses and two occupied homes. Back roads and main routes alike are dotted with blackened shells and foundations. One of the burned homes is 1 -LCB- blocks from the fire station. No one has been injured in the fires. Authorities have said most of the fires began at the back of the buildings and most were set late at night. They've refused to divulge other details. Finding patterns is the key to finding the arsonist, according to experts. `` There is always a pattern. It may be as illogical as you can imagine,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, who after 23 years with the the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Fire Department began his own fire investigating firm. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahart </PERSON>, executive secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigators </ORGANIZATION>, said patterns can be found in the time of day, the day of the week, the location, the method and other details. `` A serial arsonist will progress,'' <PERSON> Ahart </PERSON> said. `` He'll work his way up the ladder. Little fires become bigger fires and bigger fires become yet bigger fires. As they get bolder and more accustomed to what they're doing, whatever drives them to do this becomes a bigger need or addiction.'' Plainclothes state policemen driving unmarked cars now patrol <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>, and investigators have asked the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to try to develop a psychological profile of the fire starter. A member of the state fire marshal's office has moved to town. At least 200 people attended a recent town meeting called by state police to calm residents' fears. The <ORGANIZATION> Jefferson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firemen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has offered a $ 5,000 reward for information leading to the arrest and conviction of whoever is responsible. At <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>'s burned-out house, the reward poster sits amid flower pots that stood in what was the dooryard. He and his wife, son and stepdaughter scrambled out a bathroom window onto a roof and down a ladder to escape the fire that broke out at about 1:15 a.m. They lost everything. A 5-month-old <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> spaniel and a cat did n't make it out. <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>'s wife, <PERSON> Donna </PERSON>, and her daughter wo n't sleep at night unless someone is awake, he said. Blueprints already are drawn for another home on the site, but the new house will be only one story _ easier to escape. `` It's tough to live this way right now,'' said <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, 43, who manages a building materials store in nearby <LOCATION> Littleton </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>, `` before this started, was a very cohesive town, a traditional, small town where everyone would look out for each other,'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a local innkeeper. While closeness remains, `` you look over your shoulder, you are suspicious of your neighbor. It may break some bonds.'' State police Lt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said people `` are attempting to protect their own property, and we have word that people are establishing their own citizen patrols late at night to identify this individual.'' He has encouraged residents instead to call police with anything unusual. Mrs. <PERSON> Hartford </PERSON> told a story about a man who got a flat tire while driving late at night, but was afraid to leave his car until daylight. Another resident recounted how a plainclothes policeman emerged from the woods near a barn and was met by three people with guns trained on him. `` I would n't walk this street when it starts getting dark,'' <PERSON> Perkins </PERSON> said. It's difficult to convince people who feel their lives are threatened not to take action, Mrs. <PERSON> Hartford </PERSON> said. `` We're all frightened to death,'' she said. `` We do n't want to hurt anyone, but we want to protect what's rightfully ours.'' Perhaps the intensity of the investigation will drive the arsonist to leave or to stop setting fires for a time, leaving residents with only their fear. `` I've heard many people say they are not going to sleep again until this person is caught,'' said innkeeper <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Aug. 3</NOTE>
