<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv29   07-28 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 29,0642</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday July 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bills Coming Due</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation. Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The story appeared in the sports section. But like many a modern sports story, it was about finance and economics, too. After a prolonged negotiation, <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Cadigan </PERSON>, the first round draft choice of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jets </ORGANIZATION> football team, had signed a $ 2 million contract. The sticking point, according to news accounts, had been that <PERSON> Cadigan </PERSON> and his lawyer wanted most of the $ 850,000 signing bonus paid in 1988, while the maximum income tax rate is 28 percent. `` <PERSON> Cadigan </PERSON> wanted to receive a larger portion of his overall bonus this year, as the maximum rate could go up in succeeding years,'' the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported. There is a lot of that going around these days _ a sense that some long-outstanding bills will soon come due for many Americans as individuals and the country as a whole. When analysts listen to campaign promises from either party this year, they react with more than the customary skepticism. How, they ask, is anybody going to pay for these goodies when the government is already shoulder-deep in debt? `` Stop kidding us,'' says the current issue of Fortune magazine, chastising the presidential candidates for playing down the question of a tax increase. `` Everybody knows that for the deficit to come down, taxes must go up.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, who publishes the newsletter Brennan Reports on tax and investment planning, is giving advice very similar to what <PERSON> Cadigan </PERSON> got from his attorney. Normally, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> says, savvy taxpayers begin around this time of year figuring out how to defer as much income as possible past New Year's Day, in order to reduce the tax bills they will face. `` In the past, planning was usually concentrated on deferring income _ that's no longer true!'' he observes. `` There may be cases where income should be accelerated into 1988, while tax rates are low. In the future, a 28 percent or 33 percent rate may be pretty appetizing when we look back to 1988.'' It is less than two years since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> overhauled the income tax system, curbing or eliminating many tax deductions. The legislators were able to sell the bill to the public by lowering tax rates. So you might expect cries of outrage at talk of raising those rates again. But there are other forces at work as well. One is the Gramm-Rudman-Hollings bill, also enacted in 1986, that mandates across-the-board cuts in spending for government programs unless specific goals are met toward balancing the federal budget. In this election year, says <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Pecarich </PERSON>, director of tax policy at the accounting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Coopers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lybrand </ORGANIZATION>, policymakers probably can dodge the Gramm-Rudman ax with some imaginative maneuvering and optimistic assumptions. `` Next year will be a different story,'' she says. Then there are the stirrings of inflation that lately have troubled Wall Street _ and that <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, has spoken of with unusually candid concern. These inflation worries arise out of a vibrant economy in which industry is enjoying a renascence and unemployment has fallen to a 14-year low. But that near-boom has been financed to a great extent with other people's money _ in many cases, money borrowed from foreign investors to pay for goods made by foreign manufacturers. `` There is very good momentum in the economy right now,'' says <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Boltz </PERSON>, financial economist at the investment management firm of <ORGANIZATION> T. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rowe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Price </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. However, he adds, `` We have n't started to pay for this party. And we wo n't until we have a trade surplus.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri July 29</NOTE>
