<FIRST>a w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv31   07-28 0990</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 31,1018</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drought Bites Into Cherry Pies and Bean Soup, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drought has taken its toll on beans, peas and other food crops as well as chewing away at big-ticket items like corn, soybeans and spring wheat, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` The drought's greatest impacts on fruit and vegetable crops are likely to be on dry edible beans, tart cherries, green peas, sweet corn, and snap beans for canning,'' says economist <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Zepp </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> produce about 50 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sweet corn and green peas, much of which is on non-irrigated acreage,'' he says. `` <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> produces about 40 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> snap bean output, about half of which is grown on non-irrigated acreage.'' The production of vegetables grown for the fresh market tends to be concentrated on irrigated land, so the drought impact has not been so great. <PERSON> Zepp </PERSON>, writing in the August issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine, provided an appraisal of how the hot weather and drought has affected several high-value crops. Here's a summary of his analysis:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CANNED VEGETABLES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Midwestern output of green peas is about 50 percent below normal. Sweet corn and green beans are harvested later in the summer, and production depends on rainfall in the remainder of the season. Canners expect Midwestern sweet corn and green bean production to be only 70 percent to 75 percent of what had been planned, and carrot and beet production is expected to be 60 percent to 65 percent. Canners boosted prices of peas, sweet corn and snap beans by 10 percent to 20 percent in June because of anticipated production shortfalls. Most of the corn, peas and beans grown in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> are for canning. Vegetables for freezing are concentrated in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, where water for irrigation generally has been adequate for vegetable production this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>POTATOES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Hot, dry weather in June hurt development of potatoes across the Northcentral states, reducing stands and stressing plants. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimates 1988 total potato acreage at 1.27 million acres, down 2 percent from last year. The area for fall harvest is estimated at 1.06 million acres, down 3 percent from last year. The large 1987 fall crop resulted in generally lower prices, causing farmers to reduce acreage this season.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWEET POTATOES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Growers planted 93,900 acres of sweet potatoes for 1988, down 3 percent from last year. The biggest change was in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, where acreage dropped nearly 11 percent from 1987. Dry soils delayed planting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DRY EDIBLE BEANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Drought appears to have contributed to a 36 percent cut in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s dry bean acreage this year, since most of the crop is on non-irrigated land. Dry weather delayed plantings in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, which increased the chance of frost damage this fall before the crop is mature. Also, some growers shifted dry bean acreage to soybeans, hoping for higher returns. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> grows mainly navy beans, accounting for about 60 percent of last year's navy bean harvest nationwide. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> bean prices rose nearly 40 percent during the third week of June because of anticipated drought losses and smaller supplies. The July estimate of area for harvest for all types of dry beans was 1.51 million acres, down 13 percent from last year. In addition to the decline in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, large acreage reductions were reported for <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, on the other hand, reported 21,000 acres more for harvest than in 1987.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>APPLES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Production is forecast at 8.07 billion pounds this year, down 23 percent from the 1987 apple harvest. All regions expect smaller production. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, the stress on trees from last year's record crop and this year's varied bloom and set contributed to reduced prospects. Trees in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> region suffered from some winter damage, and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s crop is expected to be smaller because of spring freezes and drought.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GRAPES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> total grape harvest is forecast at 4.7 million tons, up 1 percent from last season. Raisin-type grape output is forecast at 2.15 million tons, down 2 percent from last year. Some irrigators have had water allocations scaled back, and many have switched to costly pumping of well water. Production of table-type grapes in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> is forecast at 600,000 tons, up 18 percent from last year. Tight water supplies have not affected table grape production, and growers are reporting heavy yields. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> wine grape production is forecast at 1.95 million tons, the same as last year. Drought has had little effect so far, but some acreage may undergo stress as irrigation water runs out.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TART CHERRIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Production is forecast at 207 million pounds, down 42 percent from 1987. Production in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, the largest cherry producer, was off 43 percent. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s output is down 34 percent from last year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TOBACCO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tobacco area for harvest in 1988 is estimated at 624,000 acres, up 6 percent from last year. Both flue-cured and burley showed increases, reflecting higher effective quotas for 1988. Moisture has been adequate for plant growth in much of the flue-cured belt, and yield prospects look good. But dryer conditions prevailed in the burley area, so yields likely will be reduced.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SUGAR BEETS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Estimated plantings of sugar beets were put at 1.32 million acres, up 4 percent from last season. The acreage was up in all major growing areas except <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. However, dry conditions resulted in poor germination, requiring growers to replant some fields several times. According to industry sources, more than 250,000 acres, mostly in the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, had to be replanted. In some cases, farmers may have switched to other crops having a shorter growing season or requiring less soil moisture for seed germination. According to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> analysts, sugar beet production will be substantially below last year's near-record harvest, while cane output may equal or exceed last year's level.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
