<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-28 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0564</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The economy expanded at a healthy 3.1 percent annual pace from April through June, but rising food, energy and clothing costs pushed the inflation rate to 4.7 percent, its highest level in almost six years, the government reports. Some private economists worried that the big jump in inflation reported Wednesday signaled the concluding stages of the current long economic recovery and could well result in a recession some time next year. But the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> dismissed the inflation figure as a temporary deviation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Henley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, after failing to gain control of <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has agreed to sell its <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fe </ORGANIZATION> shares to <ORGANIZATION> Itel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in a deal that would give <PERSON> Henley </PERSON> a 40 percent stake in the Chicago-based holding company. The companies valued the deal announced Wednesday at $ 1.2 billion in cash and stock. The complex transaction also calls for sale to <ORGANIZATION> Itel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Henley </ORGANIZATION>'s stock holdings in American President Cos.. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a shipping container company, and of <ORGANIZATION> Henley </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Signal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, a financing company and lessor of railroad
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Rainfall and cooler temperatures have eased the drought in some of the worst-hit parts of the country, but extreme conditions still prevail in the West, the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Rockies </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. Jitters about next week's weather held crop futures prices in check Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> where corn prices fell, soybeans were mixed and wheat was higher.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors who jumped into the agricultural commodity markets when the Midwestern drought became apparent last spring have been scrambling for the exit doors since the weather changed for the wetter, experts say. With crop conditions either static or improving, prices for future delivery of grains and soybeans have fallen precipitously. The drop in crop futures prices has spilled over into the livestock and sugar futures markets, and has prompted some economists to lower their month-old projections for 1989 food inflation from about 7 percent to 6 percent or less.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents of bank deregulation have suffered several key defeats as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> works on long-awaited legislation hailed as the most important change in banking law since the Depression. By a 35-14 vote Wednesday, the committee approved an amendment to permit mutual fund underwriting, and by a 27-23 vote it endorsed an amendment to allow underwriting of bonds which are later convertible to stock. As originally written, the far-reaching bill granted bank holding companies some new securities powers, but would have prohibited them from underwriting corporate stocks and mutual funds.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says its second-quarter earnings climbed 11 percent from a year earlier to $ 1.66 billion, setting an auto industry record for the second consecutive quarter. The profit reported Wednesday was 2.5 percent above the previous industry record the No. 2 automaker set in the first three months of this year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said its earnings, which amount to $ 3.43 a share, came on second-quarter sales of $ 22.39 billion. During the same period last year, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 1.50 billion, or $ 2.90 a share, on sales of $ 19.50 billion.
