<HEAD>Economy Shows Strong Growth, With Spurt In Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: will be led with Commerce Department report on personal
income, scheduled for 10 a.m. EDT release.</NOTE>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The economy expanded at a healthy 3.1 percent annual pace in the second quarter, according to the government, but the financial markets focused on rising food, energy and clothing costs that pushed the inflation rate during the period to a nearly six-year high. Stock and bond prices declined Wednesday after the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> released its economic growth report, which indicated inflation was at 4.7 percent annual pace in the second quarter. The government reported that the growth rate in the gross national product, the economy's total output of goods and services, was down only slightly from a revised 3.4 percent increase in the first three months of the year. But inflation, as measured by a price index tied to the GNP, registered the biggest advance since the third quarter of 1982. The GNP price index had risen at a 3.5 percent rate in the first quarter. The White House dismissed the inflation figure as a temporary deviation, but some private economists said the current long economic recovery may be coming to an end, setting the stage for a recession some time next year. `` We have had a definite upturn in the inflation rate which is a by-product of our long expansion,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The demand side of our economy is now exceeding our ability to produce, which is causing price pressures.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> already has pushed interest rates higher as a way of dampening demand and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the central bank would tighten further if inflationary pressures did not abate. In the bond market, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond lost about $ 5.60 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price and is often an indicator of interest rate trends, jumped to 9.23 percent from 9.18 percent late Tuesday. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 20.27 to 2,053.70, its lowest close since it stood at 2,052.45 on June 2. The dollar finished lower against most major currencies, while crop futures closed mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as late jitters about next week's weather offset a rally that analysts said was long overdue.
</TEXT>
