<HEAD>Giant Japanese Securities Firm To Buy Stake in Investment Boutique</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Perella </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s agreement to sell a 20 percent stake to giant <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 100 million represents a coup that could win the aggressive, young firm an ever bigger share of the lucrative international merger and acquisitions business. Other cash-rich Japanese companies have bought into large, established, capital-hungry Wall Street firms. But the investment by <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> _ <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s biggest securities house _ represents a relatively more potent capital boost to the small, six-month-old investment boutique. <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON> <PERSON> Perella </PERSON> was formed in February by two leaders of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s highly successful mergers and acquisitions operation, who quit to start their own firm. Under an agreement announced Wednesday, the two firms plan to work together on mergers and acquisitions involving Japanese, American and European companies. The transactions are expected to be handled through a joint venture company. `` This will be a very good source of business for our firm, and -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION>'s -RRB- knowledge of the Japanese market is a real advantage to our clients who are looking to sell assets to Japanese buyers,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Biondi </PERSON>, a vice president at <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON> <PERSON> Perella </PERSON>. Tokyo-based <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> had 1987 profits totaling $ 2.13 billion and a market capitalization in excess of $ 56 billion. <PERSON> Yoshihisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Tabu