<HEAD>SouthernNet, Teleconnect Agree To Form Long Distance Holding
Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new telephone holding company that will become the nation's fourth-largest long distance carrier has no plans to take on the industry leaders nationally, according to company officials. <ORGANIZATION> SouthernNet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Teleconnect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rapids </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, said Wednesday they signed a letter of intent to create a yet-to-be-named holding company that will form a long distance carrier serving about 400,000 customers. The company would have annual revenue of more than $ 400 million. Teleconnect, formed in 1979, and SouthernNet, founded in 1984, have grown rapidly, providing long distance and other telephone services mainly to businesses within their regions. Teleconnect, which made its initial public stock offering this year, operates in 21 mainly Midwestern states. The company earned $ 7.6 million, or 90 cents per share, on revenue of $ 167.8 million last year. SouthernNet operates in 10 Southeastern states and in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and earned $ 8.7 million, or 62 cents per share, on revenue of $ 228.6 million last year. Trading was halted on both companies' shares early Wednesday afternoon with SouthernNet standing at $ 20.62 -LCB- a share on the over-the-counter market and Teleconnect at $ 15 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Wednesday's joint announcement said the holding company would concentrate on regional operations and not compete directly with the big three of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>. The companies have `` high penetration in some areas and we specifically do not want to to out and try to cover the nation,'' said SouthernNet President <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabbard </PERSON>, who will serve as chairman and chief executive officer of the Atlanta-based holding company. Teleconnect chairman and chief executive <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON> will be vice chairman and president of the company. The nation's long distance market has been estimated at $ 50 billion annually, with <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T getting 72 percent. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> has about 10 percent and <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> about 7 percent, according to <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Grubman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our aspiration is not to be a national player but to be very strong regional players sharing research and development and sharing network capacities,'' <PERSON> McLeod </PERSON> said. Shareholders, who still must approve the deal, would receive one share of stock in the new holding company for each share they now hold in the regional companies. The companies also announced quarterly results Wednesday. Teleconnect reporting second quarter earnings of $ 2.6 million, or 23 cents per share, on revenue of $ 60.3 million. SouthernNet earned $ 5.9 million, or 43 cents per share, on revenue of $ 65.9 million, compared with a profit of $ 3.07 million, or 22 cents per share, on $ 55.47 in revenue during the year-earlier quarter. The latest quarter includes $ 2.42 million from SouthernNet's sale of a cellular telephone subsidiary The boards of both companies have approved formation of the new company, which remains subject to regulatory approval as well as the execution of a definitive agreement. <PERSON> Gabbard </PERSON> estimated the deal would be completed in the fourth quarter. The two companies have worked together previously, and last month announced the creation of a national toll-free service.
