<HEAD>USX Head Says Steel Unit Could Be For Sale, But No Buyers Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the steel industry enjoying a healthy revival after seven years of depression, <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is willing to sell a chunk of its steel-making USS division, according to Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON>. But so far, proposals to spin off up to 20 percent of the unit have come only from investment bankers, not actual principals, <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said Wednesday at his quarterly news conference. <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said he welcomed proposals, `` providing we were offered full, f-u-l-l, value ... and we certainly have no incentive to sell it for less than full value.'' The chairman of the energy and steel company declined to suggest a figure. `` We would n't want to restrict the imagination of potential buyers,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Corry </PERSON> said any deal probably would involve <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> making a public offering of stock in part of the steelmaking division. <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> would retain tax benefits accumulated during steel's years of unprofitable operations, said <PERSON> Corry </PERSON>, who is considered a leading candidate to succeed <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> when the chairman reaches the company's mandatory retirement age of 65 next May. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> projected 1988 steel industry shipments of 81 million tons or more, a high figure that would mean two more quarters of robust business. With demand for steel showing no signs of faltering and mills running at or near capacity, prices are rising and profits are flowing in, he said. <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said the USS division, the domestic industry's largest producer, is reconsidering an Oct. 1 price increased it announced to customers of flat-rolled steel. The timing of the price move was undermined by <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, the third-largest producer, which scheduled increases of up to 5.5 percent for Jan. 1. No. 2-ranked <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> followed <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>'s lead <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said price increases are justified even though his company is churning out profits of $ 70 per ton. `` Back in the first first quarter of this year, our prices were about 19 percent below 1981. We've picked some of that back up in the second quarter, but my guess is that we're still 12 to 13 percent below the 1981 steel prices,'' he said. `` And when we get out of this decade ... the steel prices are going to be lower than when we came into the decade,'' <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said. `` I ask you, how many manufacturing industries in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are going to get through the decade of the'80s with absolutely zero inflation in price?'' Stronger earnings in steel compensated for the diminished performance in energy for a fourth consecutive quarter as <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reported second-quarter profits of $ 213 million, or 74 cents per share, on sales of $ 4.3 billion. `` Oil carried us from 1982 through 1987,'' <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> said. `` This is the first period when earnings from energy were lower than earnings from steel.''
