<HEAD>Dollar Up in Technical Reaction to Earlier Falls; Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was slightly stronger today against most European currencies in what dealers said was a technical reaction to earlier declines. Gold was weaker. Traders said the dollar was recovering through heavy central bank intervention after it was driven down Wednesday by disappointing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product figures. `` It went down unbelievably fast Wednesday, and so I believe there is some room to make -LRB- the dollar -RRB- a little firmer today,'' said a <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> trader. `` The central banks really pushed hard on the dollar, and now it's a bit undervalued.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy grew 3.1 percent in the second quarter of 1988, less than the 4 percent rate widely anticipated. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound was quoted at $ 1.7360, compared with $ 1.7265 Wednesday. Dealers said the Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> intervened after the pound, surging on expectations of higher British interest rates, hit 3.22 Deutschmarks, its highest rate against the West German currency in two years. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's rates included: 1.8552 West German marks, up from 1.8495; 1.5340 Swiss francs, down from 1.5375; 6.2555 French francs, up from 6.2375; 2.0892 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0820; 1,370.00 Italian lire, up from 1,365.50; and 1.2085 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2070 In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 132.10. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 132.17 yen. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 432.50 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $ 433. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 428.75. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 431.25, down from $ 432.50 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid price of $ 433.78, u