<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell slightly today, but stock prices were firmer in slow trading after the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product figures for the second quarter of the year. On the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> Foreign Exchange, the dollar opened at 131.67 yen, the day's low, and was stable around the 131.70-131 .80 yen range during the morning session It edged up to close at the day's high of 132.10 yen, down 0.40 yen from Wednesday's close. Volume totaled $ 4.8 billion, slightly up from Wednesday's $ 4.3 billion. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the Nikkei Average of 225 selected issues, which posted its second biggest gain this year Wednesday by surging 434.81 points, rose another 57.52 points, or 0.2 percent, to close at 27.796.09. In the first section, 850 million shares changed hands, compared to Wednesday's 1.3 billion shares. Exchange dealers said growing concern about inflation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> put downward pressure on the dollar. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product, the broadest measures of an economy's health, grew 3.1 percent in the second quarter, down slightly from the revised 3.4 percent rate the previous quarter, according to figures released Wednesday. But inflation registered the biggest advance since the third quarter of 1982. Securities analysts discounted any major effect of the dollar's fall on the stock market `` You ca n't apply the same old principle of ` When the dollar falls, stock market also falls' any longer,'' said <PERSON> Keiichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishida </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION>.
