<HEAD>London Stocks Higher At Midday On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices rose Thursday, boosted mainly by speculative buying of selected issues. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index rose 5.2 points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,846.0 by mid-afternoon. Volume was 275.2 million shares, compared with 188.9 million shares at the same time Wednesday. The market largely ignored the pound's surge and Wednesday's news of a wider-than-expected British trade deficit in June, dealers said Instead, attention turned to speculative situations, giving selected stocks a sharp boost. Among major gainers, shares in <ORGANIZATION> Pearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> shot up 42 pence, or 73 cents, to 784 pence after trading as high as 796 pence amid a variety of rumors about the company. One rumor held that <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> might sell off its oil exploration and production operations in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. A Pearson spokesman said the company was reviewing its options in regard to the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> holding. <PERSON> Pearson </PERSON> shares also got a boost as attention focused on the publishing sector, following speculation that <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> could become the target of a takeover bid. <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> shares continued their recent run, jumping another 20 pence to 463 pence. There also were rumors that <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, controlled by publisher <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON>, could sell off its more than 20 percent stake in <LOCATION> Pearson </LOCATION> and then make a bid for Reed, dealers said.
