<HEAD>U.A.E. Leader Affirms Support for Opec Unity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto one name is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ruler of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> affirmed Thursday his nation's support for unity within the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, the official emirates news agency <ORGANIZATION> WAM </ORGANIZATION> reported. The agency, reporting the meeting between <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Zayed </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Nahyan </PERSON> and cartel Secretary-General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, quoted the U.A.E. president as saying his country `` has always been at the forefront for boosting <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> decisions and supporting the stability of the oil market.'' The report did not specifically address the controversial issue of U.A.E. oil production, but it indicated the emirates would not undermine the 13-nation cartel by adopting unilateral decisions. <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Zayed </PERSON>'s statements were made after <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> gave him a message from <ORGANIZATION> OEPC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Rilwanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> WAM </ORGANIZATION> report. Details of the message were not disclosed. The meeting was also attended by <PERSON> Mana </PERSON> <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON>, the federal U.A.E. oil minister. <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> and <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON> met earlier as oil sources said the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general sought a compromise regarding the U.A.E. claim for a higher oil production quota. <ORGANIZATION> WAM </ORGANIZATION> said only that <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> discussed with <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON> the `` latest developments in the world oil market.'' The sources, who spoke on condition they not be named, said <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>'s visit came in response to reports quoting U.A.E. oil officials as saying the country would abandon its <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production quota of 948,000 barrels of oil a day and produce about 1.5 million barrels a day. They noted <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s price monitoring committee will meet Aug. 3 in <LOCATION> Lausanne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, to discuss the oil market situation in light of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s decision to accept a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for a cease-fire in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war. The war has been casting shadows on the cartel's efforts to curb production levels and maintain an $ 18 per barrel benchmark price. Both <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> are prominent <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members and have been flouting production and pricing policies, respectively, because of the conflict. The U.A.E. demand for a higher quota is also a prominent issue for the <LOCATION> Lausanne </LOCATION> meeting of the five-member pricing committee which comprises the oil ministers of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON> has said the U.A.E.'s current quota was not fair and did not synchronize with its production potential, claimed to be 4 million barrels per day.
