<HEAD>Research Consortium Names New Chief Executive and Operating
Officers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION>, a research consortium of 14 semiconductor manufacturers in partnership with the federal government, appointed longtime industry leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Noyce </PERSON> as its chief executive officer. <PERSON> Noyce </PERSON>, once called `` the Mayor of <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>,'' is a co-inventor of the integrated circuit, a critical element in computers and other electronics. He is also the co-founder of <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and is its vice chairman. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION> board of directors, also announced Wednesday the appointment of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Castrucci </PERSON>, a top technical executive at <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> with 32 years' experience, as <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION>'s chief operating officer. <PERSON> Noyce </PERSON> said he at first took himself out of consideration because of other commitments, but `` it finally dawned on me it was far too important for someone else to do. I had to do it myself.'' With the chief executive and operating officers now in place, <PERSON> Noyce </PERSON> said he was `` confident we're going to be able to make a quick transition into full blown operations.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, is the nation's first semiconductor research consortium supported by both private industry and the federal government. <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION> will sponsor and conduct research into advanced semiconductor manufacturing processes, materials and equipment. Results of the research will be available to the 14 member companies and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> license-royalty free, and one to two years later will be available to non-members. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> appropriated $ 100 million to <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION> in this year's budget and the consortium said it is confident next fiscal year's budget will also contain $ 100 The total budget is $ 250 million annually. Semiconductors are vital parts in almost every modern electronics system _ from microwave ovens to communications satellites. The electronics industry in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> accounts for $ 230 billion in annual sales and 2.5 million jobs, <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION>'s goal is world leadership in semiconductor technology by 1993. Part of its strategy is also to work with universities around the country, and five were named last month to receive grants of up to $ 1.5 million a year for manufacturing research. Such consortiums have been successful in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> but `` have been attempted in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> without a great deal of success,'' <PERSON> Noyce </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION>'s staff in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> is now at 135 and when it is in full gear will employ 600 to 800. A large percentage of employees will be assigned from the member companies. The consortium's member companies are <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Devices </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris