<HEAD>June Gain Best in 3 Months; Spending Up at Faster Rate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans' personal income jumped a healthy 0.7 percent in June, the best showing in three months, while consumer spending rose even faster, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said that consumer spending rose 1.0 percent to $ 3.21 trillion, following a 0.6 percent increase in May. It was the biggest increase since spending shot up 1.3 percent last August. The big rise in spending is likely to be viewed as worrisome by analysts who have been looking for consumer demand to ease to allow room in the economy for production of exports. Too much consumer demand is seen as inflationary because it places a strain on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers who are fighting to lower the trade deficit. The $ 27.9 billion increase in personal incomes to $ 4.04 trillion followed a 0.5 percent rise in May, a modest 0.2 percent increase in April and a 1.0 percent jump in March. With spending rising a bit faster than income, Americans' personal savings rate fell slightly to 4.3 percent, compared with 4.4 percent in May Still, the average savings rate for the first half of 1988, 4.1 percent, is up substantially from 3.2 percent in 1987. Americans' after-tax income increased 0.8 percent in June after shooting up 2.4 percent in May. The gain in income in part reflected healthy increases in employment in June. The unemployment rate dropped to 5.3 percent last month, a 14-year low. That was somewhat offset by a $ 1.3 billion decrease in farm income in June, attributed to a $ 3.9 billion drop in federal farm subsidy payments. The department gave these details of spending: _ On durable goods, `` big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years, spending rose $ 8.6 billion in June compared with an increase of $ 2.7 billion in May _ On non-durable goods, spending rose $ 4.5 billion in June, compared with $ 4.6 billion the month before
