<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s central bank on Thursday raised its Lombard lending rate to 5 percent in a bid to bolster the mark, which has lost ground to other major currencies in recent weeks. The Lombard rate had stood at 4.5 percent since Nov. 6, 1987. The mark has been falling against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and the British pound on foreign exchange markets. Analysts said the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>'s decision, which is effective Friday, was aimed at supporting the mark and slowing the flow of capital out of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` With this measure, the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> is taking account of the development of market interest rates and tensions in the currency market,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. The Lombard rate is the interest rate charged on banks' short-term borrowings from the central bank against securities as collateral The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> left its discount rate unchanged at 3 percent, which was set June 30 after a hike of 0.5 percent. The higher Lombard rate effectively lifts the ceiling on money market rates, giving the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> room to directly tighten money market rates further if the mark shows major signs of weakening, analysts said. <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> has said the dollar's advance against the mark endangers international efforts to adjust trade imbalances in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> Thursday's announcement follows <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> decisions to raise the rate on securities repurchase deals for commercial banks. That rate has been raised three times in the last six weeks by .25 percent increments to its current 4 percent.
