<FIRST>u f PM-BudgetReview 1stLd-Writethru   07-28 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget Review, 1st Ld-Writethru,0699</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 5 grafs with comment from Miller, CORRECTING
projected deficit figure in lede from $5.6 billion to $5.9 billion.
Picks up 5th graf pvs, The drought-relief ... Also moving on
general news wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Drought Aid Could Trip Gramm-Rudman Trigger, Administration Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration estimated today that the federal deficit for the upcoming budget year would be $ 140.1 billion, $ 5.9 billion under the trigger for across-the-board spending reductions. But budget director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said too large a drought-relief package could provoke the automatic cuts. The new deficit estimate, covering the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, is $ 5.9 billion smaller than the $ 146 billion level that would force cuts to kick-in under the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law. But in presenting the estimate, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, warned that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must exercise spending restraint in granting relief to farmers and in several other areas or face the risk of triggering automatic spending cuts. `` We can not do all those things. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has got to pare down and make sure it does not go over the limit,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> told reporters at a White House briefing. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> warned that drought-relief and other spending proposals pending before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could push the deficit upward and trigger the politically painful spending cuts, which would take effect just before the November elections. The drought-relief measures now being considered in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are estimated to cost $ 4.3 billion to $ 6.6 billion. The administration wants to keep the drought package at $ 4 billion to $ 5 billion. The administration is also fighting to hold the spending line on other measures currently before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. These include anti-drug legislation, pending trade legislation and a supplemental spending bill. Under the Gramm-Rudman act, the administration is required to estimate the coming year's fiscal budget deficit by mid-August to project whether across-the-board spending cuts will take effect. The White House budget office must then adjust that estimate in October to take into account any new legislation. If such legislation pushes the deficit past the trigger amount of $ 146 billion, across-the-board spending cuts of more than $ 10 billion automatically take effect. The report today, known as a mid-session review, estimated that the deficit in the current fiscal year would be $ 152.3 billion. This estimate is still more optimistic than those of many private forecasters and the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, which is projecting a deficit of $ 157 billion for the current fiscal year. The 1987 budget deficit was $ 150.4 billion, down from the record $ 221.1 billion deficit run up in 1986. The sharp reduction last year occurred because of a one-time windfall in revenues generated by a massive overhaul of the tax law. The revised deficit estimate for the current fiscal year of $ 152.3 billion was up from the administration's February estimate that the deficit this year would be $ 146.7 billion, which would have made it lower than the 1987 imbalance. The administration blamed that higher deficit figure on increased government spending in several areas. One of the biggest over-runs occurred in the federal deposit insurance programs that protect depositors at banks and savings and loans association. The budget review said that the insurance funds would pay out $ 4.6 billion more this year than had been originally budgeted because of high failure rates at banks and thrift institutions in the depressed <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION>. The deficit target under the Gramm-Rudman legislation for the upcoming fiscal year is $ 136 billion, but the legislation says automatic spending cuts can be avoided if the government's deficit projection is within $ 10 billion of that figure. Thus, for 1989, any estimate below $ 146 billion would avoid the need for spending cuts. If the cuts did take effect, half of the reductions would come from the military and half from domestic spending programs. However, 70 percent of the domestic budget, including such programs as Social Security, has been declared off limits. Thus such programs as AIDS research and drug-law enforcement would feel the brunt of a disproportionate share of any automatic spending cut, the administration has warned.
</TEXT>
