<FIRST>r f AM-FarmSpending     07-28 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Spending,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought Won't Reduce Spending by Farmers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drought may take a bite out of the income of many farmers, but the hot, dry weather is n't expected to cut back on their spending for many production items this year, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report said Thursday. `` The drought is expected to have little impact on 1988 expenditures for seed, fertilizer and pesticides because most of these ... were applied at or before planting,'' the report said. `` Farm machinery expenditures are projected to increase again in 1988 but could be slowed by the drought.'' Spending on the fuel and electricity needed to run farms will be affected significantly by the drought, however. `` Energy expenditures for irrigation will be up, but likely will be more than offset by decreased outlays for harvesting and drying,'' the report said, a grim reminder that reduced yields _ or none at all _ mean it will cost less to run grain combines and dryers. Farmers spending on machinery increased $ 1.2 billion to $ 5.8 billion in 1987, ending seven years of decline, the report said. Net cash income of farmers _ the difference between gross cash receipts and cash expenses _ rose to a record $ 56 billion in calendar 1987. Current <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> forecasts put 1988 net cash income at $ 53 billion to $ 59 billion.
</TEXT>
