<SECOND>AM-Drought-Stranded Workers,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Seeks Relief for Migrant Workers Unable To Travel Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of migrant workers are stranded in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and do n't have enough money to return home because the drought has robbed them of a living, a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> lawmaker said Thursday in seeking federal assistance. Democratic Rep. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON>, in a letter asking <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> for emergency aid, said many migrants are in a desperate situation `` we can no longer continue to ignore.'' <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Zachariasiewicz </PERSON> said the agency `` has a plan of action'' but it wo n't be unveiled until Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, who is overseas, gives it her final approval. An announcement will be made next week. An administration source said the package would total $ 4 million to $ 5 million, but `` the final distribution is just not set on paper yet.'' The source spoke on condition of anonymity. In his letter to Mrs. <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> said: `` Migrant workers pinned their hopes on a successful harvest and invested their personal savings to search for field work. Drought conditions have dashed their hopes for employment and for recouping their financial losses. `` Because the president's emergency relief program is directed solely at the farmer level, migrant workers and their families have no safety net to relieve their conditions. Measures taken to date have allowed migrant laborers to fall through cracks.'' <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON>, a migrant worker for 23 years and the son and grandson of Mexican-Americans who followed the crops, said he still has relatives who travel from <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> to harvest sugar beets. He estimates the stranded migrant and seasonal worker population at about 10,000, but said it is difficult to get a true figure. <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> said most of the migrants are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens, and most are from along the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> border. `` Exhaused of their personal financial resources, they have no money for temporary shelter and food,'' he wrote. `` Many would like to return home, but they can not. They are broke, indebeted, stranded and dependent on the kindness and charity of local efforts.'' He said he is seeking funds to provide shelter, food and job-search assistance to migrants who want to stay in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> to help farmers salvage crops, and to give others who want to return home money for travel.
