<FIRST>r f AM-ConsumerWarnings     07-28 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Consumer Warnings,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Council Weighs Nullifying Food Warnings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House, in a move that could lead to a weakening of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s `` New Federalism'' campaign, will study whether the federal government should act more aggressively to supersede some state and local laws, an administration official said Thursday. That was the upshot of a meeting by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Domestic Policy Council, which discussed the specific question of whether <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s Proposition 65 food-labeling requirement hampers interstate commerce and thus should be overtaken by federal regulation. It's one of the toughest consumer-oriented regulations in the country, requiring warnings on any food products suspected of presenting a risk for birth defects or cancer. During his more than 7 -LCB- years as president, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has advocated a `` New Federalism'' policy aimed at relinquishing some of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s regulatory powers to states and local governments. An executive order aimed at instituting this policy contains language suggesting intervention by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> under certain circumstances, however. An administration official said no decision was reached at Thursday's meeting on whether to interfere with state and local laws and regulations requiring warnings on food packages. Instead, this official said, a White House working group was set up to consider the matter. This group would include representatives of such agencies as the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The official, discussing the meeting on grounds of anonymity, said the central question before the interagency working group is when and under what circumstances the federal government should act if it concludes that a state or local regulation harms interstate commerce. Among other things, the study group will try to determine whether Proposition 65, enacted by voters in 1986, duplicates or conflicts with the federal Food and Drug Act. Food industry officials who have criticized the state standards as unnecessary and costly, and they hailed the action as a victory. `` We think this is the formal beginning of a major policy review,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Nedelman </PERSON>, vice president for public affairs for the Grocery Manufacturers Association. `` We think we have a crazy situation on our hands, and before it gets really crazy, the government is going to take a real look at the problem.'' But environmental advocates in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condemned the council's decision. `` This is a clear industry-orchestrated sneak attack directly on Proposition 65,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON>, an attorney for the Environmental Defense Fund and a principal author of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> initiative. The proposition, the Safe Drinking Water and Toxic Enforcement Act of 1986, requires that companies give <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> consumers a `` clear and reasonable warning'' if a product contains a chemical that poses `` a significant risk'' to their health. A variety of industries, including gasoline service stations, convenience stores and chemical plants, have posted warnings about the presence of chemicals known to cause cancer and birth defects. The state, however, has granted a temporary exemption from the warning requirements for food products, drugs and cosmetics that already meet existing federal and state safety standards. The state will analyze more than 50 chemicals that could be found in these products during the next two years to determine whether warnings should be required under Proposition 65. Food industry officials contend none of their products pose a danger to consumers. But they say they fear Proposition 65 may lead to putting warning labels on food packages to alert consumers to the presence of lead, arsenic or benzene, substances that are present in minute quantities in many common products.
</TEXT>
