<HEAD>M&amp;A Activity Robust in 1st Half, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Merger and acquisition activity increased steadily during the first six months of 1988 while the dollar value of completed deals jumped 45 percent from a year ago, a financial information firm reported Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> IDD </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> said that 1,705 transactions were completed in the first two quarters, up from 1,622 in the first half of 1987. More impressive, perhaps, was that the deals this year carried a pricetag of $ 131 billion, up from $ 89.5 billion in the year-ago period, the firm said. Foreign investors snapped up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies at a rapid pace, spending $ 25 billion on acquisitions in the first half of this year, up 67 percent from $ 15 billion in 1987. IDD attributed the interest _ led by <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> _ to a weaker dollar. Despite predictions of a decrease in activity following the October market crash, leveraged buyouts moved along at a brisk clip. In the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> IDD </ORGANIZATION> said there were 77 leveraged buyouts with a total value of $ 30 billion, compared with 58 buyouts valued at $ 20 billion a year ago. In a leveraged buyout, investors borrow against a target company's assets and repay borrowed funds from the company's cash flow. The use of tender offers as a way to acquire companies also increased dramatically. IDD said such transactions were valued at $ 75.9 billion, compared with $ 35.3 billion in tender offers a year ago. In terms of number of transactions completed, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> led the pack of major investment houses by acting as financial advisor in 92 deals; followed by <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> with 77 and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> with 70. Based on dollar value, however, <ORGANIZATION> Goldman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> was No. 1, representing $ 41.72 billion in completed transactions, followed by <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION>, $ 40.4 billion, and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>, $ 34.1 billion. <ORGANIZATION> IDD </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, headquartered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, supplies the merger and acquisition information to financial and legal clients.
