<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that its second-quarter earnings slid 24.5 percent compared with a year ago, and analysts said buyer incentive programs may have compressed results more than the company expected. The nation's No. 3 automaker said it earned $ 320.4 million, or $ 1.45 per share, in the three months ended June 30 compared with $ 424.1 million, or $ 1.98 per share, in the second quarter of 1987. The depressed profits due to rebate and incentives programs were a short-term sacrifice to boost market share and improve the company's long-term competitiveness, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said. That game plan led to brisk sales, which should strengthen <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s standing in the marketplace, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said. `` You get a conquest -LRB- first time -RRB- buyer into your stable and hopefully you keep him,'' explained <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON>, auto analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The results came on sales of nearly $ 8.5 billion in the second quarter, up 32.8 percent from $ 6.4 billion in the same period a year ago. `` The profit margins were very poor considering the level of business they did in the quarter,'' said analyst <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> Lambert of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` They have been pushing heavily with incentives and the market share's gone up, but the results show the effect of it.'' `` They were a little bit under where they were going to come in -LRB- under the forecast -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> said. `` The principal reason, essentially as I read the number, was average yields per unit were down a little bit, and that reflects fleet sales, the cost of rebates and incentives ... It was essentially the incentives.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s 20.7 percent share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> truck market was up nearly two percentage points from the second quarter of 1987, the company said. Through June, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s combined <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car and truck retail sales were up 16 percent from the same period of 1987. `` We're going after a bigger base of loyal customers, because that's what it takes to succeed over the long haul,'' <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said. For the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s net earnings totaled $ 504.1 million, or $ 2.27 per share, down from $ 693.5 million, or $ 3.22 per share. The first half results include a $ 93.1 million charge for previously announced plant closings in the <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. First-half sales rose 30.6 percent to $ 16.16 billion from $ 12.44 billion a year earlier. During the second quarter, the nation's No. 3 automaker continued to hold the line on 1988 model prices, with 42 percent of the passenger cars it sells tagged below 1987 prices. `` That's paid off for us in higher market share, but we're caught in a classic case of ` margin squeeze,' and we ca n't rely on that strategy forever,'' <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said `` We have seen that the incentives, in terms of rebates, have been coming steadily down for about six months,'' <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> said. `` The basic game plan, I think, in a sense among the executives at the three large companies, is to launch the new models without any meaningful incentives.'' On Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> announced a small price increase on the Colt GT for 1989, but said it would lower prices on two other Colt models. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s credit arm, made record earnings on the increased sales volume, reporting profits of $ 61 million for the second quarter of 1988 and $ 126 million for the first six months of the year, the subsidiary announced today. The results eclipse the previous quarterly high of $ 56 million, set in the second quarter of 1987, and a six-month earnings record of $ 117 million, also set a year ago, a company statement said. On Wednesday, No. 2 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported an auto industry record second quarter, earning $ 1.66 billion, up from $ 1.50 billion in the second quarter of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest manufacturer, last week reported its second-quarter earnings _ $ 1.5 billion, compared with $ 1.17 billion in the comparable period of 1987
