<HEAD>Crop Futures Slip, Sugar Sinks; Technicals Cited</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 17th graf pvs, Sugar futures ...
with coffee prices. Picks up 18th graf pvs, The continuing ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and sugar futures prices fell sharply Thursday in trading that analysts said was inspired by technical conditions and had little to do with fundamental supply-and-demand factors. Most wheat and soybean futures also slipped lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, and coffee futures joined sugar in falling for a third straight day on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. On other markets, precious metals were lower; cattle were up while pork futures plunged; and energy futures were mixed. Thursday marked the fifth consecutive day of falling corn futures prices and the ninth straight daily drop in the price for August delivery of soybeans. But in a departure from the past three months, the weather had little impact on the markets, analysts said. Instead, they said corn traders were watching their market's open interest, a rough measure of the number of speculators who have _ in effect _ placed their bets but not collected their winnings Open interest has been running at an unusually high level in the corn market and stood at more than 244,000 contracts when the market opened Thursday. The majority of the open interest was believed to represent `` long'' positions, or wagers that prices would rise. Since prices have been falling, some players feared that many holders of those long positions were preparing to sell and either cut their losses or settle for only a slight profit. A sudden, massive sell-off would cause prices to plummet and some traders tried to beat the rush by selling ahead of it, which caused corn prices to fall sharply anyway. The selling sentiment spread to the neighboring wheat and soybean pits, causing prices to fall in those markets, too, said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s latest 6-to-10-day forecast, calling for normal rainfall next week in the drought-stricken <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, was bearish but it was not a major factor in Thursday's action, <PERSON> Spilka </PERSON> said `` I think weather forecasts are maybe contributing about half the influence right now -LRB- and -RRB- I think near-term forecasts are more important than the 6-to-10-days,'' he said. Wheat settled 4 cents to 5 -LCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.57 a bushel; corn was 14 -RCB- cents lower to 2 cents higher with September at $ 2.65 a bushel; oats were 3 cents lower to 7 -LCB- cents higher with September at $ 2.56 -LCB- a bushel; and soybeans were 12 cents lower to 15 cents higher with August at $ 7.41 -LCB- a bushel. The situation was similar in the sugar market, which ignored the bullish news of new sugar purchases by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and plummeted to its lowest level in about a month. `` This was a technically driven sell-off,'' said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON>, sugar analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Sugar futures have been extremely strong and stood at 6 -LCB- - year highs on Monday Ms. <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON> said the market fundamentals remained bullish and that the nearly 3 -LCB- - cent plunge over three days `` just gives you better bargains. Sugar for October delivery settled .53 cent lower at 10.82 cents a pound. Coffee futures continued their technically-driven decline with the September contract settling .26 cent lower at $ 1.2379 a pound. The continuing decline in the grain markets forced some speculators with additional holdings in silver and platinum futures to take profits in the metals markets so they could meet their financial obligations in the grain markets, said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Gold was more stable in its traditional role as a `` safe haven'' for investment dollars, she said On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold settled 70 cents to $ 1 lower with August at $ 432.50 a troy ounce; silver was 25.8 cents to 29.6 cents lower with August at $ 6.707 a troy ounce. Hog and pork-belly futures fell their respective daily limits of 1.50 cents and 2 cents a pound on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> because `` there's too much supply and not enough demand, period,'' said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Cattle futures followed the grains to a mixed close, <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said Live cattle were .87 cent lower to .33 cent higher with August at 66.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .93 cent higher with August at 79.75 cents a pound; hogs were 1.12 cents to 1.50 cents lower with August at 43.87 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were 1.32 cents to 2 cents lower with August at 30.95 cents a pound. Crude oil prices were little changed in quiet trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as traders waited for an upcoming <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> committee meeting. West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 1 cent to 2 cents lower with September at $ 16.15 a barrel; heating oil was .23 cent to .69 cent lower with August at 44.34 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .11 cent lower to 1.15 cents higher with August at 51.95 cents a gallon.
