<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> and the parent of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday said their after-tax profit rose strongly in the latest quarter from a year earlier, boosted by revenue gains generated by growth in passenger traffic. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest airline, reported a 134 percent jump in second-quarter profit. Its earnings advanced to $ 124.2 million, or $ 5.77 a share. The profits surged past last year's second-quarter airline earnings of $ 53 million. The company actually earned a total of $ 73.4 million, or $ 1.29 a share, during 1987's second quarter, but that figure included profits from nonairline subsidiaries it has since sold. The number of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> shares outstanding was sharply reduced during the period, to around 21.5 million in the second quarter of 1988 from 56.9 million in the year-earlier quarter. Second-quarter revenue rose to $ 2.34 billion from $ 2.07 billion a year earlier. Early this year, Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> completed the sale of its non-airline assets _ the <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> car rental agency and the Westin and <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> hotel chains. It changed its name from <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which had been intended to signify its former status as a travel conglomerate. `` These results make it clear that <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> has returned to its core business of running an airline and doing so with the talent of 63,000 committed employees,'' said Chairman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, who took over the company last December following the ouster of former chief <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>. In the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s profit surged to $ 701 million, or $ 19.12 a share, from $ 42.8 million, or 79 cents a share, a year earlier. Earnings in the 1988 first half include a $ 548 million gain from the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Westin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION>. The number of shares outstanding dropped to around 36.6 million in the first six months of 1988 from 54.0 million in the same period of 1987. First-half revenue rose 13 percent, to $ 4.44 billion from $ 3.93 billion. Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>, the third-largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline, reported a 76 percent boost in profit in the fourth quarter of its fiscal year ended June 30. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s fourth-quarter earnings jumped to $ 103.28 million, or $ 2.11 a share, from $ 58.8 million, or $ 1.21 a share, a year earlier. The results for the latest quarter include a loss of $ 1.08 million, or 2 cents a share, from the disposition of aircraft and an $ 89,000 loss from foreign currency translation. Fourth-quarter revenue rose 19.1 percent, to $ 1.87 billion from $ 1.57 billion. Analysts said the airline probably benefited from troubles at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s main competitor. Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has been beset by labor and financial problems, including a federal safety inspection of its fleet, and last week announced the layoffs of about 4,000 employees plus the elimination of 140 flights. Prior to those cutbacks, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> competed head-to-head with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> on about 70 percent of its routes. For its fiscal year ended June 30, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s profit rose to $ 306.83 million, or $ 6.30 a share, from $ 263.73 million, or $ 5.90 a share, in fiscal 1987. It was <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s first full fiscal year since its takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Revenue for the fiscal year increased to $ 6.92 billion from $ 5.32 billion.
