<HEAD>Major Maker of Ozone-Destroying CFC's Starts Producing
Alternatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a major producer of chemicals that are destroying the earth's protective ozone shield, said Thursday its plans were underway to begin producing alternatives to the chemicals by this fall. The company will modify an existing facility in <LOCATION> Montague </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, to produce alternatives to fully halogenated chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, by as early as October. <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s are non-toxic, non-flammable compounds that <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> helped develop in the 1930s. They are widely used as refrigeration fluids, cleaning solvents, plastic form blowing agents, and outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as aerosol propellants. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> announced last March that it planned to move away from the production of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s in the next 12 years. The alternatives, to be used as blowing agents for a variety of insulation and cushioning applications, could be commercialized in five years, said company spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Forte </PERSON>. First the chemicals, HCFC-141b and HCFC-142b, must be tested to ensure they are not toxic. `` The ozone depletion rate of the new compounds is more than 95 percent less than existing compounds,'' <PERSON> Forte </PERSON> said. HCFC-141b is being evalutated as a replacement to CFCs used as insulating materials in refrigerators, refrigerated trucks and rail cars, homes and buildings, and as cushioning for automobile seats, furniture and bedding. HCFC-142b is being tested in the manufacturing of polystyrene insulation and polyolefin insulation and packaging. The plant will be one of three producing <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> alternatives. `` While our ultimate goal is to develop and commercialize non-ozone depleting products, we will continue to search for interim alternatives that will enable us to reduce dependence on fully halogenated CFCs in a stepwise fashion,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glas </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>'s Freon Products Division. About 2.3 billion pounds of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds are made worldwide each year, with more than 2,000 <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> employees producing about 25 percent of the total. The company says it gets $ 600 million annually from <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> sales, about 2 percent of its total sales revenue. Last fall in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, major producers agreed on a treaty, now signed by 31 nations but ratified only by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, agreeing to cut <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production 20 percent in 1992 and another 30 percent in 1998.
