<HEAD>Reports 2nd-Qtr Profit More than Tripled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that its second-quarter profit more than tripled with an assist from a one-time gain from sale of two subsidiaries. The company also announced it has opened its books to about 10 different bidders seeking to buy <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the unit involved in exploration and production and refining and marketing that was put up for sale in May. For the three-month period ending June 30, the diversified energy company posted net earnings of $ 154 million, or $ 1 per share, compared with $ 46 million, or 24 cents per share, during the same period a year ago. The latest results include a one-time gain of $ 23 million related to the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of Gebr. Broere, a European shipping and storage company, and <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> heating oil retailing company. Revenue for the quarter rose 5.4 percent to $ 3.9 billion from $ 3.7 billion a year earlier. For the first six months of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said its net income nearly tripled to $ 217 million, or $ 1.38 per share, from $ 75 million, or 32 cents per share, for the first half of 1987. Six-month revenue rose 6.8 percent to $ 7.9 billion from $ 7.4 billion. `` The core of businesses which will comprise <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> following the sale of the oil company reported strong profits with pipelines, automotive, packaging, chemicals and agricultural and construction equipment recording increases over last year,'' <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said. Each bidder for <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> gets one week to review the information, available through Aug. 25. The first round of bids is due Sept. 30. `` We've been very encouraged by the interest,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON>, chairman and chief operating officer of <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION>, said during a news conference. <PERSON> Ketelsen </PERSON> said potential buyers may bid on major segments or as a whole. He declined to disclose names of the bidders, who signed confidentialty agreements. When <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> announced plans to sell <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, it said it would use the proceeds to help pay its hefty $ 8.5 billion debt. Analysts have estimated that the sale could fetch between $ 5 billion to $ 7 billion. For the second quarter, the <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> unit recorded net income of $ 147 million, compared with $ 76 million for the same quarter in 1987.
